<html>
<head><title>The Heritage Foundation Internship Program</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"></center>
<h2><center><i>Internship Program</h2><br></i></center>
<b><i><center>1995-96 Information and Application Form</b><br></i>
<hr width=75%><br></center>
<P>
	The Heritage Foundation was founded in 1973 "to formulate and promote conservative public policies based on the principles of free enterprise, limited government, individual freedom, traditional American values, and a strong national defense."   A non-partisan tax-exempt institution, it is now one of the largest and most influential research and educational foundations in the United States, providing national, state, and local decision-makers with information that is concise, timely, and relevant to the current policy debate.<p>

	In the early 1980s Ronald Reagan described Heritage as the "feisty new kid on the block." Today, according to House Speaker Newt Gingrich, "Heritage plays a major role in developing the ideas that are going to make America's success possible in the 21st century."<P>

	Located in the nation's capital, The Heritage Foundation offers both summer and academic year internships.  These programs are intended to introduce bright and innovative undergraduate students to the policy-making process, involve them in the important questions and issues of the day, and encourage them to become active and effective participants in public affairs.<br><center>
<p>
[ <a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/intern_program/app.exe">Download</a> the Application | <a href="mailto:personsb@heritage.org">E-mail</a> Beth Persons for more information, or call her at (202) 546-4400]
</center>
<p><b>Download Instructions:</b> To download the application, a self-extracting Zip file, click on the link above, and save the file (app.exe) to your hard drive. In File Manager, double click on app.exe, and unzip. Open the unzipped file in your word processing program.<p> 
<hr>

<i><h3><center><u>The Heritage Internship Program</h3></center></u><p>


	Internships vary depending on the department to which the participant is assigned.  In general, applicants should possess strong writing abilities, a talent for research, and excellent communication skills.  During the internship program, participants will attend weekly discussion seminars on policy issues and political thought that are designed to augment their day-to-day activities.  In order to further enrich the internship experience, program participants are invited and encouraged to attend Heritage Foundation lectures, policy-briefings, and Third Generation Meetings.
<P>
<u><b>Summer Internships</u></B>:  Each summer, The Heritage Foundation selects approximately thirty-five interns to work full-time in various departments.  This program offers a weekly salary of $250.00.
<P>
<u><b>Academic Year Internships</u></b>:  During the academic year, a smaller number of interns are chosen to work either part or full-time in various departments.  This program offers a stipend of $8.00  per diem to cover expenses.
<P>
Departments offering internships:
<P><center></i>
<a href="#aca">Academic Programs</a><br>
<a href="#asian">Asian Studies Center</a><br>
<a href="#bus">Business Relations</a><br>
<a href="#coal">Coalition Relations</a><br>
<a href="#dom">Domestic and Economic Policy Studies</a><br>
<a href="#exec">Executive Offices</a><br>
<a href="#foreign">Foreign and Defense Policy Studies</a><br>
<a href="#govt">Government Relations</a><br>
<a href="#lect">Lectures and Seminars</a><br>
<a href="#newmaj">New Majority Project</a><br>
<a href="#polrev"><i>Policy Review</i></a><br>
<a href="#pubrel">Public Relations</a><br>
</center><p>  
<a name="aca"></a><b>Academic Programs</b> maintains active contact with students, scholars and academics throughout the nation.  Interns assist in supporting this network, the Bradley Resident Scholars Program, The Salvatori Center for Academic Leadership, and the Heritage Internship Program.  A research intern is hired to assist in-house Bradley Fellows.  Interns must possess excellent communication and research skills, and have an interest in conservative ideas and principles.
<P>
<a name="asian"></a>The <b>Asian Studies Center</b> addresses the challenges and opportunities the United States faces in Asia and the Pacific.  Interns conduct factual research (economic, demographic, military) for the ASC Statistical Handbook and provide research and clerical support for analysts who are writing papers.  Applicants should have a demonstrated ability to absorb large amounts of information and an interest in international relations with an emphasis on Asian, security, and economic issues.
<P>
<a name="bus"></a><b>Business Relations</b> maintains contacts with business leaders throughout the country.  Interns provide support for the staff and help coordinate special events for corporate representatives.  Applicants should have a background in business and economics.
<P>
<a name="coal"></a><b>Coalition Relations</b> oversees Heritage's liaison to 2,000 policy groups, advocacy organizations, and scholars in the United States and abroad.  Coalition Relations serves and leads the conservative movement through annual conferences, monthly working groups, and strategic resource materials, such as The Insider newsletter and the Guide to Public Policy Experts.  Interns write abstracts for The Insider, attend and help coordinate conferences and meetings, and provide research and administrative assistance for publishing and database-building projects. Interns must be knowledgeable about current public policy issues and have a strong interest in conservative movement politics. 
<P>
<a name="dom"></a>The <b>Domestic and Economic Policy Studies</b> department analyzes those areas most directly affecting the economic and social well-being of U.S. families, businesses, and communities.  Heritage's Roe Institute for Economic Policy Studies is the Foundation's economic research arm, focusing on federal tax, budget, regulatory, and environmental policy.  Interns may be assigned to work with a specific analyst or may work as part of a team of interns to provide assistance to departmental staff.  Interns must have strong research and writing skills.  A background in economics and an interest in the legislative process are also desirable.
<P>
<a name="exec"></a>The <b>Executive Offices</b> of The Heritage Foundation consist of the offices of the President, the Executive Vice-President, Special Events, and Development.  Interns are in day-to-day contact with Heritage members while gaining an overview of the structure and administration of the Foundation.  Interns must be mature, have a strong commitment to conservative principles, and have excellent communication and organizational skills.
<P>
<a name="foreign"></a>The department of <b>Foreign and Defense Policy Studies</b> incorporates a wide range of general and area studies.  Interns are assigned to a specific analyst, but this does not preclude their occasional assistance with group or departmental projects.  Intern tasks vary and may include:  basic clerical work, researching topic areas, attending hearings, and writing short papers for analysts.  Interns must have studied foreign policy, international relations, economics, or political science, and are usually nearing the end of their undergraduate career or are in graduate school.  Interns assigned to regional specialists must have language proficiency in the region of study (Spanish, Russian, etc.).
<P>
<a name="govt"></a><b>Government Relations</b> delivers timely and accurate analysis to The Heritage Foundation's primary target:  Congress.  Interns are assigned to work with an individual director from one of the following areas:  Executive liaison, Senate liaison, House liaison, the Governors' Forum, or the U. S. Congress Assessment Project.  Interns conduct research, prepare memos and letters, and write brief notes on hearings and meetings.  Interns should have a fundamental knowledge of the American political process and a familiarity with current issues in public policy.  Political experience on campaigns or with other conservative organizations is helpful.  
<P>
<a name="lect"></a><b>Lectures and Seminars</b> coordinates Heritage lectures, Third Generation meetings, and a variety of other special programs.  Interns assist staff in researching projects, maintaining files, and planning events.  There is ample opportunity for interns to attend a wide variety of conferences and briefings to gain a broad knowledge of the conservative policy community.  Interns must be well organized and have good interpersonal skills.  
<P>
<a name="newmaj"></a>Begun in 1989, the <b>New Majority Project</b> is Heritage's minority outreach program.  It works primarily with the black and Hispanic communities on issues of mutual concern such as welfare reform, crime, revitalizing inner cities, and education reform.  As interns are responsible for research on a variety of issues, writing ability is important.  In addition, interns help plan meetings and luncheons, prepare mass mailings, and attend conferences.  Since interns may be given independent research projects, they must know how to obtain information from multiple sources, and possess good research skills.
<P>
<a name="polrev"></a><p><i><b>Policy Review</b></i> is Heritage's quarterly journal of conservative opinion and debate.  Interns are hired by the Editor to conduct special research projects, such as compiling a list of great conservative quotations or writing a feature article on the world's greatest conservative movies.  A publishing intern is also hired to assist in advertising and distribution.  Interns provide general office support for the editorial staff.  Interns must have a talent for research and writing, and have computer skills.
<P>
<a name="pubrel"></a>The <b>Public Relations</b> department is both multimedia and multifaceted, tailoring information and opinion for both the print and broadcast media.  Interns are integrated into the department and work with all staff members on various assignments.  Interns are usually journalism, communications, or public relations majors, or have worked with their campus publications or radio stations.  
<p><center>
[ <a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/intern_program/app.exe">Download</a> the Application | <a href="mailto:personsb@heritage.org">E-mail</a> for more information ]
</center>

