<li>The Federal Budget
<li>Tax Policy
<li>Welfare Reform
<li>Curing America's Social Ills
</ul>
<p>
<img src="blueball.gif" alt=""><b> <a href="#foreign">Foreign and Defense Policy</a></b>						
<p>	<ul>

<li>U.S. Foreign Policy Challenges in the Post-Cold War Era
<li>Defending America's Interests
<li>The Growing Importance of Asia
<li>U.S.- China Relations: Challenges and Opportunities
</ul></ul>
<p>





<CENTER><a name="washington"><H3>WASHINGTON'S MARKETPLACE OF 
IDEAS</H3>
</A>
</CENTER>

<b>Edwin J. Feulner, Jr., Ph.D.</b>, <I>President</I>
<ul>
A veteran of the national political scene, Feulner recently served as Vice Chairman of the <a href="/taxcom/reptoc.html">National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform</a>. A leading conservative strategist and thinker on issues from American foreign policy in the post-Cold War era to how Washington works, Feulner is the former director of the House Republican Study Committee. Feulner also serves on the boards of several other foundations and research institutes.  He has served as Chairman of several governmental commissions and is on the boards of George Mason University and Regis University. He also served as a consultant to President Reagan on domestic policy issues. Feulner holds a bachelor's degree from Regis University, an M.B.A. from the Wharton School and a Ph.D. from the University of Edinburgh. He is the author of <I>Looking Back</I> and <I>Conservatives Stalk The House</I>.    
</ul><P>

<b>Phillip N. Truluck</b>, <I>Executive Vice President</I>
<ul>
Truluck is Heritage's chief operating officer, responsible for overseeing all day-to-day operations. During 1982 and 1983, he served on the Executive Committee of the President's Private Sector Survey on Cost Control, more commonly known as the Grace Commission. Prior to joining Heritage in 1977, he was on the staffs of Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., and Rep. Ken Blackwell, R-Ohio, and served as Deputy Director of the Republican Study Committee. He is a founding director of the Board of Directors of the Center for International Private Enterprise, an affiliate of the National Endowment for Democracy, where he served from 1983 to 1991.

</ul><P>
<b>David Mason</b>, <I>Vice President, Government Relations</I>
<ul>
An advisor to House Republicans when they framed their "Contract With America," Mason is a leading authority on national politics and congressional reform. He is the former Director of Heritage's U.S. Congress Assessment Project, which studied institutional problems facing Congress  and offered recommendations to solve them. Under Mason's direction, Heritage published a seminal book, <I>The Ruling Class: Inside the Imperial Congress</I> (1993). A former Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense and longtime veteran of Capitol Hill, Mason previously served as Staff Director to then-House Minority Whip Rep. Trent Lott, R-Miss., and in a variety of positions for national, state and local political campaigns. 

</ul><p>
<b>Herb Berkowitz</b>, <I>Vice President, Public Relations</I> 
<ul>
An award-winning public relations executive who has played a key role in making Heritage 
America's best-known public policy organization, Berkowitz can speak on how to work with the 
media and mobilize public support for an idea or cause.
</ul><p>
<b>Jeb Bush</b>, <I>Trustee</I>
<ul>
Bush is a leading Florida businessman and Chairman of the Foundation for Florida's Future, a state policy institute.  One of five children of the former President and first lady Barbara Bush, he was the 1994 Republican nominee for governor of Florida. Bush has long been active in the state's civic and political affairs, serving as Florida's Secretary of Commerce and for two years as Chairman of the  Republican Party of Dade County. He is a graduate of the University of Texas at Austin, where he majored in Latin American Studies. He later served as a Senior Executive for Texas Commerce Bank. Bush also is co-owner of the National Football League's Jacksonville Jaguars.  
</ul><p>
<b>Hugh Newton</b>, <I>Senior Counsel, Public Relations</I>
<ul>
The president of his own public relations firm, Newton joined Heritage as Public Relations Counsel in 1977.  <I>National Review</I> Founder William F. Buckley Jr. has called Newton "the best promotion man in the United States." He is a two-time recipient of the Silver Anvil Award, the public relations' industry most prestigious honor, and also has earned a Freedom Foundation George Washington Honor Medal for his work. Newton is an expert on how to market ideas and work with the nation's news media. He earned a B.A. in journalism from Washington and Lee University.
</ul><p>
<b>Cheryl Rubin</b>, <I>Director, Public Relations</I>
<ul>
Rubin is a recipient of the Silver Anvil Award,  the public relations' industry highest honor. She is a former Director of Public Relations for United Way of America and Senior Account Executive  for the public relations firm Carl Byoir and Associates, serving in both the New York City and Atlanta offices. Rubin also is a former Producer for ABC TV's Good Morning America  and WRNG, a talk radio station in Atlanta. She hold a bachelor's degree in journalism/broadcast news from the University of Georgia.    
</ul><P>
<b>Adam Meyerson</b>, <I>Vice President, Educational Affairs; Editor, <a href="/heritage/p_review/welcome.html">Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship</a></i>
<ul>
Meyerson, who has served since 1983 as Editor of Heritage's flagship publication, <I>Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship</I>, also supervises the foundation's academic programs, including the Bradley Fellows program, the Henry Salvatori Center for Academic Leadership, and lectures and seminars. Meyerson is a former Editorial Writer with <I>The Wall Street Journal</I> and Managing Editor of <I>The American Spectator</I>.  He is co-editor of <I>The Wall Street Journal on Management</I> (Dow Jones: Irwin). He earned his B.A. from Yale University and did doctoral studies at the Harvard University Graduate School of Business.

</ul>
<p>
<b>Robert Blatz</b>, <I>Vice President, Administration and Chief Financial Officer</I>
<ul>
Blatz oversees the foundation's day-to-day financial operations as well as its administrative, computer services, personnel, accounting and payroll departments. He also assists with the investment and management of the foundation's invested funds. Since May 1993, Blatz served as Chief of Staff to Heritage President Edwin Feulner. Before joining Heritage, he  
was an Army officer stationed in Italy, Germany and the United States. Blatz earned a bachelor's degree from the U.S. Military Academy at West Point. 
</ul><p>
<b>John Von Kannon</b>, <I>Vice President and Treasurer</I> 
<ul>
Von Kannon is former Publisher of  <I>The American Spectator</I>, which he now serves as a  Contributing Editor and a member of its Board of Trustees. He previously served as Vice President of the Pacific Legal Foundation in Sacramento and as President of Russell & Von Kannon, a Chicago-based marketing and consulting firm. A graduate of Indiana University, Von Kannon is a Senior Fellow at The Foundation for Research on Economics and the Environment in Bozeman, Montana.
</ul><p>
<b>Scott O'Connell </b>, <I>Director, Development</I>
<ul>
O'Connell has fifteen years experience in fundraising and marketing. He has been instrumental in making Heritage the most broadly supported think tank in America. He currently specializes in estate planning and charitable giving. O'Connell, who has also worked at both the U.S. Department of Commerce and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, received a bachelor's degree in economics from Penn State University. 
</ul><p>
<b>Richard Allen</b>, <I>Chairman, Heritage's Asian Studies Center Advisory Council</I>
<ul>
Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs during the first year of the Reagan administration, Allen writes and lectures on U.S.-Asian policy and serves as Chairman of Heritage's Asian Studies Center Advisory Council.  A former member of the President's Task Force on U.S. Government International Broadcasting, Allen serves as a Senior Fellow at the Hoover Institution and has been affiliated with The Center for Strategic and International Studies.  He is President of the Richard V. Allen Co., a Washington-based consulting firm.
<p>
The Richard V. Allen Company, (202) 737-2824
</ul><p>
<b>William Bennett, Ph.D.</b>, <I>Distinguished Fellow in Cultural Policy Studies</I>  
<ul>
Bennett, former U.S. Secretary of Education and National Drug Control Policy Director, examines how government policies and programs affect American culture and, in turn, how American culture affects government policies and programs. Bennett is the author of the national bestseller <I>The Book of Virtues</I> (Simon & Schuster). A former Chairman of the National Endowment of the Humanities, Bennett serves as Co-Director of Empower America. Bennett earned his Ph.D. from the University of Texas and his J.D. from Harvard University. 
<p>
Contact:  Gail Helmkamp, (202) 452-8200
</ul><p>
<b>Jim Burnley</b>, <I>Chairman, Heritage's Roe Institute for Economic Studies Advisory 
Council</I>
<ul>
Contact:  (202) 371-5718
</ul><p>
<b>Elaine L. Chao</b>, <I>Distinguished  Fellow </I> 
<ul>
The former President and Chief Executive Officer of United Way of America, Chao helped restore the well-known charitable organization's membership, finances and public confidence.  Her distinguished career also includes service as Director of the Peace Corps, where she established the first outreach to the newly independent states of the former Soviet Union. Chao also served as  Deputy Secretary of the U.S. Department of Transportation, Chairman of the Federal Maritime Commission, and Vice President of  BankAmerica Capital Markets Group in San Francisco. She holds an M.B.A. from Harvard Business School and an undergraduate degree in economics from Mount Holyoke College.     
</ul><p>
<b>Jack Kemp</b>, <I>Distinguished Fellow</I>
<ul>
One of the nation's leading conservative thinkers, Kemp served as Chairman of the <a href="/taxcom/reptoc.html">National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform</a>. A long-time champion of supply-side economics and "empowerment" strategies to help the poor, Kemp served as Housing and Urban Development Secretary during the Bush administration.  A former nine-term congressman representing Buffalo, N.Y., he was a 1988 candidate for the Republican presidential nomination.  <p>
Contact: Kara Noe, (202) 452-8200
</ul><p>
<b>Edwin Meese, III</b>, <I>Ronald Reagan Fellow in Public Policy</I>
<ul>
Former U.S. Attorney General Meese was among President Reagan's most important advisors.  As Chairman of the Domestic Policy Council and the National Drug Policy Board, and as a member of the National Security Council, he played a key role in the development and execution of domestic and foreign policy.  During the 1970s, Meese was Director of the Center for Criminal Justice Policy and Management and Professor of Law at the University of San Diego.  He earlier served as Chief of Staff for then-Gov. Reagan and was a local prosecutor in California. He also is a Distinguished Visiting Fellow at the Hoover Institution, Stanford University, and a Distinguished Senior Fellow at The Institute of United States Studies, University of London. <P>
Contact: Keppler Associates Inc., (703) 516-4000
</ul><p>
<b>Mary Anne Carter</b>, <I>Director, Congressional Relations/U.S. Senate </I> 
<ul>
In addition to her extensive Senate experience, Carter served as  Director of Research for the Dole for President primary campaign where she supervised, coordinated and directed all research on campaign-related issues. Prior to that she served as Legislative Aide to Senate Judiciary Committee member Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and worked in the office of the late Sen. John Heinz of Pennsylvania. She also served as Campaign Manager to then-Rep. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., in 1992. A frequent guest speaker at George Washington University's  Political Management School, she holds a bachelor's degree  in political science from West Virginia University in Morgantown.
</ul><P>

<b>Karen Miller</b>, <I>Director, Executive Branch Liaison</I>
<ul>
Miller serves as the principal contact with the White House and Cabinet-level agencies, and oversees the foundation's <a href="/heritage/jobs/jobs.html">Job Bank</a>, which helps place conservatives in public policy positions in the Washington area.  She speaks frequently on domestic policy issues, with an emphasis on women and politics, the family, Congress, and current events.  A former Special Assistant to Vice President Quayle, Miller is the founder of the Conservative Women's Network, a monthly professional meeting for rising and mid-level conservative women.  She also serves as the <a href="/heritage/cyberwel.html">CyberPersonality</a> on the Heritage Internet website. Miller earned her B.A. and J.D. from The Catholic University of America.
</ul><p>



<b>Matthew Spalding, Ph.D.</b>, <I>Director of Lectures and Educational Programs</I>
<ul>
An expert in American government, Spalding is Heritage's liaison to colleges, universities and other academic organizations. He oversees Heritage's lecture, internship, Salvatori Fellows, and "Third Generation" programs as well as other educational workshops and seminars. Spalding previously served as Heritage's manager of academic programs. He is a former  Senior Policy Analyst for The Claremont Institute, a conservative think tank based in southern California. He holds a bachelor's degree from Claremont McKenna College and a master's and doctorate from the Claremont Graduate School.
 </ul><p>
<b>Dr. Kenneth  R. Weinstein </b>, <I>Director, Government Reform Project</I>
<ul>
Weinstein's research focuses on such topics as term limits, campaign finance, political reform, ending taxpayer-funded lobbying, and organized labor's use of union dues for political activities. Prior to joining Heritage, Weinstein served as Director of Research at the New Citizenship Project, a Washington, D.C.-based public policy group dedicated to limiting the role of government and other government reform issues. He holds a master's degree from the Institute for Political Studies in Paris and a Ph.D. in political science from Harvard University.  
</ul><P>

<b>Marshall Wittmann</b>, <I>Director, Congressional Relations/U.S. House of 
Representatives</I>
<ul>
A former top lobbyist for  the Christian Coalition, Wittmann also served in President Bush's Department of Health and Human Services as Deputy Assistant Secretary for Human Services Legislation. A veteran of Capitol Hill, Wittmann also has served as a Legislative Representative with the National Association of Retired Federal Employees and as a Public Affairs Specialist for the National Treasury Employees Union. He holds master's and bachelor's degrees from the University of Michigan.
 </ul><p>
<b>Cloyd Laporte III</b>, <I>President, Town Hall </I>
<ul>
Laporte, President of  <a href="/townhall">Town Hall</a>, Heritage's on-line Internet service that acts as a clearinghouse for conservative policy organizations. Town Hall is a joint venture of  Heritage and <I>National Review</I> magazine. Laporte  previously served as Director of Special Projects for the New York City-based Lexis Counsel Connect, an on-line service for attorneys. He holds a J.D. from the University of Chicago.
</ul><P><hr>
<center><b>FEDERALISM: RESTORING POWER TO STATES AND THE 
PEOPLE</b></center>
<p>
<b>Lewis Gayner</b>, <I>Vice President, External Relations</I>
<ul>
Gayner oversees the foundation's outreach to the business community, policy groups, and state and local government officials.  Prior to joining Heritage, he served as Vice President for Government Relations for the Washington, D.C., office of Dow Chemical Corp., and before that as Dow's Director of Regulatory and Legislative Affairs. He also held a variety of marketing, public affairs and management  positions during his 33 years with the company. Gayner earned his M.B.A. from  Stanford University.  

</ul><p>
<b>Thomas Atwood</b>, <I>Director, Coalition Relations</I>
<ul>
Atwood coordinates Heritage's outreach to more than 2,000 scholars worldwide and some 400 non-profit organizations, with special emphasis on free-market oriented state think tanks. He serves on the board of  the State Policy Network and directs numerous strategy meetings, policy forums, and management training seminars on wide-ranging topics. Atwood previously served as Executive Editor of <I>Policy Review</I>, Heritage's magazine. He earned an M.B.A. and an M.A in public policy from Regent University. 
</ul><P>
<b>Douglas Seay</b>, <I>Director, The Project on Federalism and the States</I>
<ul>
An authority on federalism, the 10th Amendment and state-federal relations, Seay coordinates Heritage's effort to help states take back power and responsibility from the federal government. He works closely with the nation's governors to ensure their voices are heard on public policy matters affecting  the states. A former Deputy Director of  Foreign and Defense Policy Studies for Heritage, he  previously held a fellowship at Harvard University's Center for Science and International Affairs and taught international relations at Brown University. Seay is a graduate of Georgetown University's School of  Foreign Service and a former Foreign Service Officer.
 </ul><p>
<b>Bridgett Wagner</b>, <I>Director, Business Relations</I>
<ul>
Wagner develops innovative ways to get the business community more actively involved in debates over public policy. She also coordinates activities of the foundation's Physicians Council, a group of more than 700 doctors working to reform the nation's health-care system. A 15-year veteran of Heritage, she previously served as Director of Development and as Speechwriter and Special Assistant to Heritage President <a href="/heritage/staff/feulner.html">Edwin Feulner</a>.  Prior to joining Heritage, Wagner was Assistant to the President of the National Center for Policy Analysis in Dallas. She holds a bachelor's degree in economics from the University of Dallas.
</ul>
<p>

<hr>
<center><a name="economy"><h3>THE ECONOMY AND SOCIETY</h3></a></center><P>
<b>Stuart Butler, Ph.D.</b>, <I>Vice President and Director, Domestic and Economic Policy 
Studies</I>
<ul>
Butler is a nationally recognized specialist on ways to solve America's social and economic problems. He is co-author of  <I>The Heritage Consumer Choice Health Plan</I> and <I>Out of the Poverty Trap: A Conservative Strategy for Welfare Reform</I>, and author of <I>Enterprise Zones: Greenlining the Inner Cities</I> and <I>Privatizing Federal Spending</I>.  The British-born Butler is an Adjunct Fellow at the National Center for Neighborhood Enterprise and holds a Ph.D. in American economic history from St. Andrews University, Scotland.
</ul><p>
<b>Angela Antonelli</b>, <I>Deputy Director, Economic Policy Studies</I>
<ul>
A former advisor to Vice President Dan Quayle's Council on Competitiveness, Antonelli  coordinates the foundation's research on budget, tax, regulatory, labor and environmental policy. She formerly worked at Lewin-VHI Inc., a leading health-care econometrics firm in Fairfax, Va.  Antonelli was Assistant Branch Chief in the White House's Office of Management and Budget with responsibility for reviewing  regulations and information collection for the U.S. Departments of Labor, Treasury, and Housing and Urban Development. A graduate of Cornell University, she earned her master's degree in public affairs from Princeton University.

</ul><P>
<b>Robert Moffit, Ph.D.</b>, <I>Deputy Director, Domestic Policy Studies</I>
<ul>
A 17-year veteran of Washington policy-making, Moffit is a former U.S. Department of Health and Human Services Deputy Assistant Secretary and senior Office of Personnel Management official. He specializes in health-care policy and coordinates Heritage's research on poverty, welfare, crime, education, and family issues.  Moffit earned his Ph.D and M.A. from the University of Arizona. 
</ul><p>
<b>John Barry</b>, <I>Economics Policy Analyst</I> 
<ul>
Barry examines how federal fiscal and regulatory policies affect the economy at the national, community and household levels. He specializes in financial sector regulatory policy, determining the effect regulation has on the efficient delivery of financial products to American consumers and businesses. A former Heritage Research Assistant, Barry also has written on federal tax and budget issues. He holds a B.A. with honors in economics and government from the University of Notre Dame and is pursuing graduate studies in economics at George Mason University. 
</ul><p>
<b>William Beach</b>, <I>John M. Olin Senior Fellow in Economics</I>
<ul>
An expert on federal tax and spending policy, Beach uses sophisticated econometric modeling to show how the economic decisions of Washington's policy-makers affect families and businesses. 
Beach, who served as an economist for the state of Missouri from 1981-1985 under then-Gov. John Ashcroft (now a U.S. Senator), also is a former top economist for Sprint Corp. From 1990 to 1995, Beach served as President of the Institute for Humane Studies in Fairfax, Va. He  holds a master's degree in history and economics from the University of Missouri-Columbia. 
 
</ul><p>


<b>Denis P. Doyle</b>, <I>Senior Fellow in Education</I>
<ul>
An internationally recognized expert on education issues and a leading advocate of school choice programs, Doyle oversaw two national education reform projects -- the Education Voucher Project and the Experimental Schools Project -- as Assistant Director of the National Institute of Education. A fixture with prestigious think tanks since 1980 -- The Brookings Institution, American Enterprise Institute and the Hudson Institute -- Doyle has  written numerous books, including <I>Investing in Our Children: Business and the Public Schools</i>,  <I>Winning The Brain Race: A Bold Plan to Make Our Schools Competitive</I>, and <I>Reinventing Education: Entrepreneuership in America's Public Schools</I>.  He is a graduate of the University of California at Berkeley with a bachelor's and a master's degree in political theory.  
 
</ul><p>
<b>Patrick Fagan</b>, <i>William H.G. FitzGerald Senior Fellow in Family and Cultural 
Issues</I>
<ul>
A former Deputy Assistant Secretary of Health and Human Services during the Bush administration, Fagan is one of the nation's leading authorities on the American family, illegitimacy's social effects, juvenile crime, religion's role in public policy, welfare, and adoption reform. He previously served as a Legislative Analyst for Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind., and as a Senior Director of the Child and Family Institute at the Free Congress Foundation. A former clinical psychologist and family counselor, Fagan was trained in psychology at the University College of Dublin. 
 </ul><P>
<b>Carrie Gavora</b>, <i>Health Care Policy Analyst</i>
<ul>
Specializing in health care policy, Gavora previously served as legislative assistant and principal staff advisor on health policy to Sen. Frank H. Murkowski, R-Alaska. In addition, she acted as chief advisor to the senator in his capacity as a member of the Senate Finance Committee, and was a professional staff member on the Senate Committee on Veterans' Affairs. She holds a bachelor's degree in political science from The Catholic University of America.
</ul>
<P> 
<b>Scott Hodge</b>, <I>Grover M. Hermann Fellow in Federal Budgetary Affairs</I>
<ul>
Hodge is the editor of <I>Rolling Back Government: A Budget Plan to Rebuild America</I>. This seminal Heritage report presents major recommendations to Congress for truly transforming the role and size of the federal government. He also is the primary architect of <I>Putting Families First</I>, a family tax cut and deficit reduction strategy that received strong support in Congress. The idea behind the congressional plan for giving families a $500-per-child tax credit had its origin in his research. Hodge, who has examined state and local tax policy and privatization issues, earned his bachelor's degree from the University of Illinois. </ul><p>
<b>Daniel Mitchell</b>, <I>McKenna Senior Fellow in Political Economy</I>
<ul>
Mitchell is Heritage's chief expert on tax policy and related economic issues. He previously served as an economist examining budgetary and tax matters for then-Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., ranking minority member of the Senate Finance Committee.  In 1995, he served as a Staff Economist for the National Commission on Tax Reform and Economic Growth. A former Director of Tax and Budget Policy at Citizens for a Sound Economy, Mitchell served in 1989 on President Bush's Independent Agencies Transition Team, analyzing the Federal Reserve System.  Mitchell is a co-host (along with his wife, Nancy) of  "Mitchells in the Morning," a popular public affairs show on National Empowerment Television. A Ph.D. candidate in economics at George Mason University, he has a master's degree in economics from the University of Georgia.
</ul><p>
<b>Christine Olson</b>, <I>Policy Analyst</I>
<ul>
As policy analyst for the Thomas A. Roe Institute for Economic Policy Studies, Olson provides statistical analysis and econometric modeling for key research areas such as education, welfare, crime, the federal budget and taxation. She previously served as a Legal Assistant for the Rutherford Institute. A 1996 Abraham Lincoln Fellow in Constitutional Government for the Claremont Institute, Olson holds a bachelor's degree in American government from the University of Virginia. 
</ul><p>
<b>Robert Rector</b>, <I>Senior Welfare and Family Issues Analyst</I>
<ul> 
One of  the nation's leading authorities on the U.S. welfare system, Rector examines the gamut of issues  surrounding welfare reform, family  breakdown and how to fix America's social ills. The  author of <I>America's Failed $5.4 Trillion War on Poverty</I>, a comprehensive examination of  U.S. welfare programs, Rector has done extensive research on the dollar cost of welfare as well as welfare's role in undermining families. An expert on the political process, Rector also is co-editor of <I>Steering the Elephant: How Washington Works</I>.  He has a B.A. from the College of William and Mary and an M.A. in political science from Johns Hopkins University.
 </ul><p>

<b>Adam Thierer</b>,  <I>Alex C. Walker Fellow in Economic Policy</I> 
<ul>
One of the nation's leading advocates of telecommunications deregulation, examines how government regulations hurt American business and global competitiveness. His work, which helped shaped the congressional debate on telecommunications reform and privatization issues focuses on communications policy, antitrust law, and the risks and costs associated with environmental regulation. He holds a bachelor's degree from Indiana University and a master's in international business management from the University of Maryland.
 </ul><p>
<b>Mark Wilson</b>, <I>Rebecca Lukens Fellow in Labor Policy </I>
<ul>
Wilson specializes in labor and employment policy, wage and benefit trends, job training programs, and workplace safety and health issues. He examines regulation and the role of government in labor-management relations. Wilson is a former Senior Economist at the U.S. Department of Labor, where he worked for 13 years in the Office of the Assistant Secretary for Policy. He is a graduate of Kent State University and has pursued graduate studies at George Washington University. 
</ul><p>
<hr>
<center>
<a name="foreign"><h3>FOREIGN AND DEFENSE POLICY</h3></a></center>
<p>
<b>Kim Holmes, Ph.D.</b>, <I>Vice President and Director, Foreign and Defense Policy 
Studies</I>
<ul>
Holmes is one of Washington's foremost authorities on foreign policy and  the challenges facing America in what he calls the "Age of Chaos." He is the principal architect of Heritage's influential foreign policy blueprint, <I>Restoring American Leadership</I>, which addressed the nation's changing strategic global interests in the post-Cold War world. Holmes earned a Ph.D. and an M.A. from Georgetown University.
 
</ul><p>
<b>Thomas Moore</b>, <I>Deputy Director, Foreign Policy and Defense Studies</I>
 <ul>
A former Professional Staff Member on the Senate Armed Services Committee, is well-versed in all areas of U.S. foreign and defense policy, including U.S. global alliances, ballistic missile defense, arms control, defense spending, and the appropriate use of the military. Moore also served two years in the Defense Department, and as Legislative Assistant for defense and foreign policy to former Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo. A graduate of The Citadel, Moore studied in France, and earned a master's degree in national security affairs from Georgetown University. He was an officer in the U.S. Army Reserve, Armor Branch, and was honorably discharged as a Major in 1993.
 
</ul><P>
<b>Ariel Cohen, Ph.D.</b>, <I>Senior Analyst in Russian and Eurasian Studies</I>
<ul>
Cohen is one of Washington's leading authorities on the politics, economics and law of Russia and the former Soviet Republics. A regular commentator on the Voice of America, Cohen has served as head of the Soviet Policy Group at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University, where he  earned his Ph.D. He received his L.L.B. at Bar Ilan University Law School in Israel and is a member of the Israeli Bar.

</ul><P>


<b>John Hillen, Ph.D.</b>, <I>Defense and National Security Analyst</I>
<ul>
A decorated Gulf War veteran, Hillen is an expert on U.S. military operations  and international peacekeeping missions such as the one in Bosnia. He also specializes in conventional force issues such as threat assessment, alliance structures, conventional force planning, and combat readiness. He is a former Regular Army Officer and still is active in the U.S. Army Reserve. Hillen previously served as a Research Scholar at the University of Oxford in England, where he earned a doctorate  in international relations. He also holds a master's degree in War Studies from Kings College, London.
</ul><P>
<b>Bryan Johnson</b>, <I>Policy Analyst, International Economic Affairs</I>
<ul>
Johnson is an expert on U.S. foreign aid and trade policy. He is author of  <I>The Index of Economic Freedom</I>,  an influential comparative survey that measures the level of economic freedom in more than 140 nations. Johnson previously served  as Senior Editor and Writer at The Whalen Co. and conducted research at Smick Medley International Inc.  Johnson earned his bachelor's degree from the University of Tampa.

 </ul><p>
<b>Ambassador Charles  M. Lichenstein</b>, <I>Distinguished Fellow</I>
<ul>
Ambassador Lichenstein served as Alternate U.S. Representative to the United Nations for Special Political Affairs from 1981 to 1984, and more recently as Co-Chairman of the U.S. Commission on Improving the Effectiveness of the United Nations.  Lichenstein is an expert on the United Nations, intelligence, terrorism, and the U.S. role in world affairs.  A graduate of Yale University, he has taught at the University of Notre Dame, Yale University and Albertus Magnus College.
 </ul><p>
<b>James Phillips</b>, <I>Senior Policy Analyst, Middle Eastern Affairs</I>
<ul>
Phillips, who has nearly two decades experience  examining Middle East and Persian Gulf political and security issues, serves on the Board of Editors of the <I>Middle East Quarterly</I>. A former Research Fellow at the Congressional Research Service and the East-West Center, Phillips earned a B.A. from Brown University and an M.A. and M.A.L.D. in international security studies from the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University.

</ul><P>
<b>Brett Schaefer</b>, <i>Jay Kingham Fellow in International Regulatory Affairs</i>
<ul>
Schaefer is responsible for examining such issues as intellectual property rights, international economic treaties and agreements, foreign aid, and the proper role of international organizations like the United Nations. He previously served as research assistant in the foreign and defense policy studies department at Heritage. A graduate of Florida State University, Schaefer will earn a master's degree in international development and economics from American University.
</ul><p>
<b>Baker Spring</b>, <I>Senior Defense Analyst</I>
<ul>
A former advisor on defense and foreign policy issues to two U.S. Senators, Spring is an expert on defense policy and budget issues, as well as arms control. He has special expertise on missile defenses and chemical and biological warfare policy. A graduate of Washington and Lee University, Spring received his M.A. in national security studies from Georgetown University.

 </ul><p>
<b>John Sweeney</b>, <I>Latin American and Trade Policy Analyst</I>
<ul>
Sweeney examines the advantages of expanding free trade throughout the Americas, especially to Chile, Venezuela and Argentina. He has written extensively on the political and economic stability of Latin America and on how to combat the drug trade and organized crime in the region. The founder and long-time editor of the influential Venezuelan newsletter <I>Ven Economy</I>, Sweeney also reported on Latin American affairs for the <I>Journal of Commerce, Business Week, Newsweek</I> and <I>The International Herald Tribune</I>, among others.  Sweeney, who served as a consultant for major U.S. corporations in Latin America, has written speeches for past Venezuelan presidents.  He is a graduate of Kent State University.
 </ul><p>




<center>
<b>ASIAN AFFAIRS</b></center>
<p>
<b>James Przystup, Ph.D.</b>, <I>Director, Asian Studies Center</I>
<ul>
Przystup is a specialist on U.S.-Japan and U.S.-Sino relations. He is a former Director of Planning for Asia-Pacific Security Strategy (1991-94) for the U.S. Department of Defense. Przystup served on the State Department's policy-planning staff  (1987-91) as Deputy Director of the U.S. Presidential Commission on U.S.-Japan Relations, and as IBM's Manager for Governmental Programs for the Asia-Pacific region.  He earned his Ph.D. in diplomatic history and master's degree in international relations from the University of Chicago. 
 </ul><p>
<b>Ambassador Harvey Feldman</b>, <I>Senior Fellow in U.S.- China Relations</I>
<ul>
Ambassador Feldman examines U.S policy toward the People's Republic of China (PRC), the Republic of China (ROC) on Taiwan, and Hong Kong. A former foreign service officer whose career spanned more than three decades and three continents, Feldman also served as Director of  Republic of China Affairs in the State Department. In that post, he created the American Institute in Taiwan, which continues to represent the United States in the ROC. He also was one of the drafters of the Taiwan Relations Act and later served as Ambassador to Papua New Guinea and as the Alternate U.S. Representative to the United Nations. Among his publications are <I>Taiwan in A Time of Transition</I>, and <I>Constitutional Reform and the Future of the Republic of China</I>. 
</ul><p>
<b>Richard Fisher</b>, <i>Asian Affairs Analyst</I>
<ul>
Fisher is one of Heritage's most knowledgeable analysts on the Asia-Pacific region. He specializes in strategic issues, such as the future of U.S. security alliances in Asia, and has expertise on Korea, the Philippines, Cambodia, Vietnam, and U.S. policy toward the South Pacific. He has traveled throughout Asia, serving as an election observer in the Philippines, South Korea and Taiwan, and  has testified before both houses of Congress. Fisher graduated from Eisenhower College with a B.A. in international relations. 
</ul><P>
<b>Robert O'Quinn</b>, <I>Asian Trade and Economics Analyst</I>
<ul>
O'Quinn specializes in international trade and investment issues, focusing on the World Trade Organization and  Asian Pacific Economic Conference. He is one of Washington's foremost authorities on the economies of  Japan, Australia, New Zealand and Singapore. O'Quinn also  served as an economist for the Federal Reserve System's Board of Governors and the Federal Trade Commission.  He earned his M.B.A. and B.A. from  the University of Georgia.
</ul><P>
<b>Stephen Yates</b>, <I>China Policy Analyst</I>
<ul>
A former China analyst for the National Security Agency, Yates focuses on U.S. relations with the Peoples' Republic of China and the Republic of China on Taiwan. In January 1991, Yates joined the Department of Defense  (Ft. Meade) as a language analyst and was recruited for work in the Commerce Department to assist with the Secretary's Business Development Mission to China. He also served in the Commerce Department's Office of China, Hong Kong and Mongolia, and in the Office of Intelligence Liaison. Yates received a master's degree in China Studies and International Economics at the Johns Hopkins University Paul H. Nitze School of Advanced International Studies (SAIS).
 </ul><P>
<center><a href="#top">Return to top</a></center>
<p>
<I>For more information about Heritage Speakers</I>
<P>
