<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Articles of Interest</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="crscweblogo.gif" WIDTH="461" HEIGHT="166" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="videonoise-purple.gif" WIDTH="463" HEIGHT="5" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4><IMG SRC="bluenew.gif" WIDTH="40" HEIGHT="29" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0"><A HREF="bydesign.html">By Design: A profile of Center Director Dr.
Steve Meyer</A></H4>
&quot;As important as it is for Meyer and his colleagues to articulate precisely
what their views are in order to establish some credibility in the mainstream
scientific community, it may be equally important for them to establish
firmly what their views do not represent. That may be the greatest obstacle
they face - not being grouped with the marginal characters of the origins
debate.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="greenfinger.gif" WIDTH="53" HEIGHT="26" ALIGN="LEFT" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><IMG SRC="transballfirered.gif" WIDTH="12" HEIGHT="12" ALIGN="BOTTOM"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><B><A HREF="pearcyreview.html">The Knee Bone Connected
to the Thigh Bone: </A></B>An in-depth review of Michael Behe's <I>Darwin's
Black Box  </I>by Nancy Pearcy</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4><BR>
<IMG SRC="transballfirered.gif" WIDTH="12" HEIGHT="12" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"><IMG SRC="new.gif" WIDTH="31" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0">One of three new articles on religion and politics by Center co-director
Dr. John G. West, Jr.</H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H5><A HREF="lewismat.html">C. S. Lewis and the Materialist Menace</A>,
from an address delivered on July 15, 1996 as part of the annual C. S. Lewis
Institute at Seattle Pacific University.</H5>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4><IMG SRC="transballfirered.gif" WIDTH="12" HEIGHT="12" ALIGN="BOTTOM"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">Especially for Biology teachers: <A HREF="pandas.html">Of
Pandas &amp; People</A></H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H5>In this intellectual and cultural climate, knowing how to teach biological
origins can be exceedingly difficult. When respected scientists disagree
about which theories are correct, teachers may be forgiven for not knowing
which ones to teach. ---- It is against this backdrop of challenge and opportunity
that the publisher offers this supplementary text, <A HREF="pandas.html"><I>Of
Pandas and People: The Central Question of Biological Origins</I>.</A> The
purpose of this text is to expose your students to the captivating and the
controversial in the origins debate.</H5>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4><CENTER><IMG SRC="videonoise-purple.gif" WIDTH="463" HEIGHT="5" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H4>
<H2><CENTER>Works by Discovery Fellows</CENTER>
</H2>
<H4></H4>
<H3><CENTER><A HREF="behearts.html">Dr. Michael Behe</A><BR>
<A HREF="Dembskiarts.html">Dr. William Dembski</A><BR>
<A HREF="meyerarts.html">Dr. Steve Meyer</A><BR>
<A HREF="westarts.html">Dr. John West</A></CENTER>
</H3>
<H4></H4>
<H4><CENTER><IMG SRC="videonoise-purple.gif" WIDTH="463" HEIGHT="5" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H4>
<P><CENTER><BR>
<A HREF="aboutcrsc.html"><IMG SRC="aboutcrsc.gif" WIDTH="71" HEIGHT="35"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><A HREF="crsc.html"><IMG SRC="crscweblogo.gif"
WIDTH="110" HEIGHT="35" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><A HREF="crscfellows.html"><IMG SRC=
