<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>December 18, 1996</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>
 <LI> For twelve days in November, French truck drivers went on strike demanding early retirement, shorter working hours, and more pay. They did not merely refuse to work, as is their right, but set up over 200 blockadesat ports, on freeways, and around major cities and oil refineries. Road transport was massively disrupted, stocks of food and gas ran low, and foreign truck drivers, held hostage in the blockades, were compelled to live in their cabins without washing. One British driver who protested was admitted to intensive care after being severely beaten up by French truckers. Throughout the entire crisis, the government insisted that it would not "use force" to break the blockades. It thereby admitted that it was not prepared to fulfill its duty to uphold the rule of law. The settlement with the truckers will cost $200 million, and the country now faces hundreds of millions of dollars in claims from companies abroad who were severely hit. The French economy also suffered severely for the second time in a yearfrom a strike. But this is merely the inevitable tribute which a decadent political system must pay to any interest group willing to trample the common good.

<P>
 <LI>The suspense if over. The winner of the Bad Writing Contest, sponsored by <I>Philosophy and Literature</I>, a journal at Johns Hopkins University, is the following sentence from Roy Bhaskar's <I>Plato etc: The Problems of Philosophy and Their Resolution</I>: "Indeed dialectical criticism realism may be seen under the aspect of Foucauldian strategic reversalof the unholy trinity of Parmenidian/Platonic/Aristotelian provenance; of the Cartesian-Lockean-Humean-Kantian paradigm, of foundationalisms (in practice, fideistic foundationalisms) and irrationalisms (in practice, capricious exercises of will-to-power or some other ideologically and/or psychosomatically buried source) new and old alike; of the primordial failing of western philosophy, ontological monovalence, and its close ally, the epistemic fallacy with its ontic dual. . . ." Mr. Bhaskar's stem-winder goes on for 58 more words, but you get the drift.
</blockquote>


