<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>December 14, 1996</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>
 <LI>


Don't cry for Disney, <I>pace</I> the omnipresent editorial cartoons of a brave Mickey Mouse facing down a Chinese tank  la Tiananmen Square. Michael Eisner's decision to go ahead with Martin Scorsese's biopic about the Dalai Lama, over the objections of China, merely demonstrates that he knows what the real currency of Hollywood is. Disney may lose the opportunity to build an amusement park near Shanghai and the chance to show Disney films to a billion Chinese, but what all that lost money couldn't buy is prestige. For accidental culture reasons, Tibetans have cachet that other victims of Communismsay, Latvianslack. Had Disney scrapped Scorsese's film, Eisner & Co. would have had to face the wrath of Richard Gere and all the other pseudo-Buddhists in Shangri-la. Getting snubbed at a party is a wound that can't be healednot by all the tea in China.
<P>
 <LI>Brian Peterson and Amy Grossberg are the 18-year-old college freshmen who went to a motel in Delaware so that Amy could give birth to their child, then tossed him in a dumpster, where he was found, dead, the next day. The pair have been charged with first-degree murder, which could carry the death penalty. But why is what is they did so much more heinous than what a doctor might have done a few hours earlier, in a partial-birth abortion? The best line on this ugly affair belongs to George Will: "Could Delaware choose to execute the two by inserting scissors into the bases of their skulls, opening the scissors, inserting suction tubes and sucking out their brains? Of course not. The Constitution forbids choosing cruel and unusual punishments."
</blockquote>


