<p>


<h3>
June 5, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
Qualifying Welfare Reform
</h2>
<P>
Guest Commentary by Rep Mark Neuman<P>

<P>This week in the House, a very important issue will be debated about a welfare reform plan known as W-2 Wisconsin Works.  
<P>While this plan is certainly about welfare reform, it is also about a much bigger, perhaps much more important issue.  Its about taking power out of the hands of Washington bureaucrats and giving it back to the people.  It is about whether you control what goes on in your state, or whether the Washington bureaucrats will micro-manage every facet of your lives.  When the House passes this bill this week, we take the first major step toward saying "no" to Big Government and federal bureaucrats and saying "yes" putting power back in the hands of the people.
<P>Governor Tommy Thompson of my state has written a welfare reform plan which, I believe, could easily serve as a model for all states to follow.  
<P>This plan was debated for 18 months in Wisconsin.  It was the subject of countless public hearings and meetings.  And then it was overwhelmingly endorsed and passed by both Houses of the Wisconsin legislature  with bipartisan support  both Democrats and Republicans put their stamp of approval on this welfare reform plan.  
<P>But now, many inside the beltway want Washington bureaucrats to tear it apart.  
<P>Washington bureaucrats have grabbed so much power from the states recently,  that Wisconsin needs federal approval before the plan is allowed to be implemented.  That is why I have introduced legislation in the House that allows this plan, which President Clinton himself called "one of the boldest yet," to be put into action in Wisconsin.
<P>While I believe Governor Thompsons welfare reform plan is an excellent one, my legislation doesnt force any other state to adopt it.  It simply clears the way for Wisconsin to move ahead with its own welfare reforms.  
<P>This welfare reform plan was researched, written, debated and passed into law by the citizens of Wisconsin and their elected representatives.  It underwent the scrutiny of numerous public hearings and 18 months of public debate.  And as I mentioned, it was overwhelmingly passed with bipartisan support in the Wisconsin legislature.  
<P>Each House passed it with at least a two-thirds vote.  Further, Governor Thompsons welfare reform plan was enthusiastically endorsed by President Clinton in his weekly radio address just three weeks ago.
<P>But as I said, regardless of the merits of this bill, this legislation represents a much bigger issue: and that is the issue of returning power back to you  the people.
<P>When I came to this Congress in 1995  along with 72 other freshmen  we had two very specific goals in mind: 
<ul>
<LI>balance the budget; 
<LI>and reduce the size, scope, power and influence of the federal government. 
</ul>
<P>We were given a mandate from the people to get Washington off their backs and reduce the burdens and regulations Washington routinely imposes upon them.  My constituents are tired of mandates from Washington; they are fed up with the massive tax burden; and they are sick of Washingtons wasteful spending habits that put their children and grandchildren further and further into debt.  
<P>But this freshmen class is changing the way Washington works.  As I mentioned several weeks ago on this program, we are making great strides in balancing the budget and reducing wasteful Washington spending.  And this week the Senate takes another try at passing a constitutional amendment to balance the federal budget  a measure which I wholeheartedly support.
<P>And now, with the legislation I have introduced this week, this Congress is taking a very important step in taking power and  influence out of the hands of Washington bureaucrats and returning it to you, the people who sent us here.  
<P>Some would have you believe that only the folks in Washington can have a monopoly on compassion.  Only they can truly see what the people out in the country really need.  Only Washington bureaucrats are fit to determine the needs of the people in Wisconsin and elsewhere.
<P>Folks, thats just silly.  Governor Thompson, along with a bipartisan effort of both Democrats and Republicans in Wisconsin approved this welfare reform plan.  They know what is best for the people they represent, not the bureaucrats in Washington who never have to face the consequences of regulations they impose.  
<P>But now the Washington bureaucrats cant stand not having their fingerprints on this welfare reform plan.  They want to review every detail.  They want to prescribe for you and for me what is best for us.
<P>This issue of welfare reform, perhaps more than any other, demonstrates the need to strip Washington of the immense power it now holds.   
<P>When we pass this welfare reform measure, it will open the door for other states to say "no" to mandates from Washington and "yes" to the wishes of the citizens. <P>


<blockquote>
<p>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote>   
