<h3>
May 30, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Elite Hits Justice Thomas Again"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<p>

<P>Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas was invited to speak next month at the Thomas G. Pullen Creative and Performing Arts School in Maryland.  This week, school officials say they have now "uninvited" Justice Thomas.  They have told him not to address the schools June 10 awards ceremony. The reason: because of  threats of a protest.
<P>``Several parents and other community members ... expressed their concern about a possible visit by Justice Thomas and in fact, threatened to stage some kind of protest, Chris Cason, a spokesman for the Prince Georges County school system in suburban Maryland, said Wednesday.
<P>In short, Maryland school officials have told a member of the United States Supreme Court he is suddenly no longer welcome at their event because the school system is now worried about even the threat of a protest from several people.  What the leaders of this school system have done is shameful. They have dishonored their original commitment to Justice Thomas and by doing so they have dishonored themselves as well as the school system they are supposed to represent. They have chosen to cower to threats of a few rather than stand on the principle of their original commitment.
<P>The action by Marylands Prince Georges County school system sends a chilling message to students. In effect what the school system says by this is that children must heed the bullying threats of the few in order to get along. It says children must put aside doing what is right in favor of doing what is safe. The action signals to children that freedom of speech for the many can be shouted down even by the threatened protest of an elite few.
<P>Of course, it is no accident that the uninvited Justice is Clarence Thomas, who is, by the way, one the most principled jurists ever named to the bench.  You see, unlike the leaders of this Maryland school district, Justice Thomas is not politically correct. His actions are not dictated by the threats of the radical few. In decision after decision on the bench, he has proven an unwavering loyalty to one thing: the United States Constitution. Because of that, almost daily, Justice Thomas is pummeled by the liberal media which hates the idea of a black conservative holding a such a powerful position.
<P>But theres one thing in particular that Justice Thomas has going for him: he doesnt care what they think. In a meeting several months with liberal reporters who complained about his position on the issues, Justice Thomas told them, "Im here to stay. Deal with it!"
<P>Deal with it. The character of Justice Clarence Thomas has been horribly and ignobly assassinated by the establishment elite and yet this man lives.
<P>The action of the Prince Georges County, Maryland, school system proves one thing: there are two kinds of public officials: those who cower before the shrill of an elite few and those who act according to principle. Pity the students: the former have defrauded these children the right to hear the latter.<P>


<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"><
