<h3>
May 29, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"the Jury Did Not Believe the President"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<p>
<P>Last Week, President Clinton went into a tirade before the cameras, accusing Bob Dole of raising the character issue.  Over the weekend President Clinton was busy down-playing the active duty military defense his attorneys want to use against the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit.  Yesterday President Clinton went before the cameras to remind the voters that he was not on trial in Arkansas.  Bob Dole need not utter a word about it. With each action, President Clintons character is becoming his own third rail.
<P>Before convicting Susan McDougal, her former husband James McDougal and Arkansas Governor Jim Guy Tucker, the jury in the Whitewater trial heard taped testimony from President Clinton.  It is extraordinary for a sitting president to testify in such a trial.  That testimony was critical to the defense.  The McDougals were former partners of Bill and Hillary Clinton.  At the very least, the presidents testimony ought to have led to the acquittal of Susan McDougal.  Instead the jury returned 24 guilty verdicts against the each of the defendants.  The president testified and yet the jury did not believe him.
<P>Were told jury members even prayed before reaching their decision. With yesterdays conviction, Arkansas Governor Jim Guy Tucker  a Democrat  said he will resign by mid July.  In doing so, he chose not to try and run the state from the "big house" but instead to surrender his post to Lt. Governor Mike Huckabee  a Republican.  That conviction and subsequent resignation alone breaths new life into an issue which has dogged this Administration since the beginning.  After all, the president testified, and the jury did not believe him.
<P>Now the voters will see Whitewater as a warning to check the White House silverware.  Now the Congress will see Whitewater as a green light to pursue its own investigations with little risk of finger pointing over partisanship.  Now reporters will see Whitewater as an opportunity to compete for the Pulitzer prize.  But more than anything else, yesterdays Whitewater convictions give instant credibility to the efforts of special prosecutor Kenneth Starr. Why? Because the president testified and the jury did not believe him.
<P>Now Starr will be free turn his attention to the one most vulnerable figure in this case  first lady Hillary Clinton. Already a compelling question is being asked in the minds of those familiar with this case.  It is a question establishment players may find too indelicate to ask. So Ill ask it.  Did Hillary Clinton perjure herself?  Now, mind you, that is not a question for Bob Dole to ask.  Whitewater is not an issue to mingle with a presidential race designed to run on issues.  If Whitewater does prove the undoing of President Clinton, it will happen because of Bob Doles obvious silence than were he and his campaign to attempt to force the issue. Now Dole can boldly proclaim real issues without ever mentioning Whitewater. All because the president testified and the jury did not believe him.
<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"><
