<h3>
May 27, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"God Is the Answer for the 21st Century"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

<P>

<P>On this Memorial Day we remember those who have given their lives so that America may remain a free and independent nation. That question  whether we will remain a free and independent nation  as relevant at the close of what has been called the American Century as it was at the beginning of this Century. Only now the threat to Americas future is not coming from an ancient European order, nor Hitlers National Socialists, nor the evil empire of Communism. The external threat comes from Moslem fundamentalists who wish to destroy the concept of the nation state, the Chinese and Japanese military/commercial complex which seeks to overrun the rest of the world by economic invasion, as well as from the United Nations which seeks to destroy the concept of sovereignty.
<P>As we pray for those who have served their country well this past Century and before, let us call to mind those who assisted their country in unpopular causes. As painful as it was for the families whose loved ones were killed in the Great World Wars, they nevertheless had the esteem of the community because a member of their family was killed in pursuit of what was believed to be a great cause by the populace. 
<P>Pity those families who had loved ones killed in Vietnam, or who served America silently in the Cold War. There was little community comfort for those killed in the unpopular Vietnam war and as to the cold war, its many victims remain largely unknown because they served as silent agents of America in this undeclared conflict.
<P>And while we are at it, let us call to mind those who now serve their nation in unpopular locations from Bosnia to Macedonia to Haiti. Some will not return and because these conflicts lack popular support back home, the families involved will not enjoy the sort of support from mediating institutions which was forthcoming during the World Wars or even the Korean conflict. 
<P>This dark Century is ending with many of the names and locations with which the 20th Century began. We have by no means fought the wars which ended all wars. Indeed there are a record number of conflicts worldwide, many of them brutal civil wars where there seem to be no good guys or bad guys or even any rational cause at stake. 
<P>For the deaths of those Americans we commemorate on this day not to have been in vain, this nation must get back to the understanding that there will be no peace without a change in mens hearts, and there will be no change in mens hearts without God. As we head toward the 21st Century, mans synergistic co-operation with God will alone bring the tranquillity and order we all seek. If only God will grant our leaders the wisdom to understand that reality.<P>


<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
<center>
