<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<br>[ <a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a> | <a href="/townhall/columnists/weyrich/i-date.html">Previous Commentaries</a> | <a href="/townhall/columnists/">Columnists</a> ] 
<h3>
May 24, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Why Clinton is Winning in the Polls"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>


<P>Remember those grade school stories of long ago about George Washington telling his father, "I cannot tell a lie. I chopped down the cherry tree," or Abraham Lincoln reading books by the light of the fire in his familys log cabin?
<P>Well if the latest ABC News/Washington Post poll is correct, you can forget all of that. 
<P>When asked if having someone of sound moral character was important in electing a President, only 22% of the respondents said yes. When asked if having a President who understood the problems of people like you was the most important factor in choosing a President, 77% responded in the affirmative.
<P>No wonder Bill Clinton is killing his rivals in the polls. In the same survey, 57% said he deserved another term in the White House. 
<P>The American people now want a President who feels their pain, not a President who has the strength of character to lead the nation. I guess that is why Bill Clinton will get by with asking that the Paula Jones lawsuit be delayed because he is Commander-in-Chief and thus is eligible to invoke a law passed at the time of World War II.  The law Bill Clinton is hiding behind was aimed at preventing a GI in a fox hole from being sued because he didnt send a payment for an appliance on time. 
<P>At a time when Admiral Boorda supposedly killed himself to avoid shame, Bill Clinton has no shame and the public thinks it is great. I guess if their President has no standards, they can excuse their own behavior somehow.  
<P>If moral character means next to nothing to Americans then no wonder Bill Clinton is Americas favorite. 
<P>Bill Clinton does tell people what they want to hear. He is for the gas tax repeal. He is for Wisconsin Governor Tommy Thompsons welfare plan. He is for the bill to permit states to ban same sex marriages. He is for the balanced budget. He supports all the things the rest of us do. Never mind that his Administration has been in the opposite camp on all these issues. He passed the gas tax he now seeks to repeal. He vetoed the same sort of welfare reform Thompson has initiated. His administration has been in the forefront of supporting the homosexual agenda. He has vetoed the balanced budget. But reality doesnt matter. As long as Clinton says the right things, never mind what he does. 
<P>Yes, Bill Clinton is obviously the right man for these times. Times when apparently honesty and truth and integrity and morality take a distant second place to feeling good. One thing Bill Clinton can do better than anyone else, no matter how bad things really are, is make us feel good. Chelsea is such a lucky kid to have a father like Bill.
<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
