<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 19, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Preempting the FDA Power Grab"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>


<P>
<P>

<P>
I am not a chess player but it seems to me that Philip Morris has dealt a rather decisive blow to the plan of food and drug czar David Kessler to assert jurisdiction over the tobacco industry. <P>
Philip Morris has announced that it will seek federal legislation to make it a crime to sell tobacco to kids under age 18. Vending machines would be banished. Sale of single cigarettes would also be forbidden. Sampling would not be permitted except in areas where minors are denied access. Retailers would have to certify that they and their employees will enforce the law. <P>
The plan would also ban tobacco products from T-shirts and hats. There would be tobacco free zones where advertising tobacco products would not be permitted. No advertising would be allowed in any transit vehicle or in terminals. Tobacco products could not sponsor any sporting event where there is a significant youthful audience. <P>
Philip Morris Vice President Steve Parrish challenged President Clinton to support this legislation and to drop what Parrish calls the unconstitutional efforts of the FDA to assert jurisdiction over tobacco products. The President can avoid years of costly litigation, Parrish said, by getting on board this legislation and getting the FDA to drop its rule making procedure. Now, clearly, we will see if President Clinton wants to do something about the problem of teenage smoking or if he just wants to expand the power of one of his favorite government agencies. <P>
As commendable as the Philip Morris initiative is, still it federalizes a matter which ought to be left up to the states. But even if the states were to adopt all of the suggestions of the Institute of Medicine, whose recommendations Philip Morris followed in coming up with their legislation, there is still no substitute for parental guidance and parental example. <P>
If adults are really concerned about teenage smoking, they ought to take it seriously when they learn that their children are smoking. They ought to stop smoking themselves. Laws, especially federal laws, are no substitute for parental responsibility. <P>
While we would rather see Congress pass a law than a federal agency seize power in an unconstitutional fashion, members of society should turn less to federal laws and more to themselves if societal problems are going to be solved. <P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
