<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 16, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"New Spin on Natural Laws"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>
<center>
by Mark Weaver
</center>

<P>
The past hours discussion of the issue of gay marriage may make you wonder where our culture is heading.  What wont people do for a thrill?  What natural laws wont they flout?  Well, wait till you hear this!
<P>Frightful new attractions are popping up across the country this summer, luring children and flouting the law of ...GRAVITY.  
<P>A new roller coaster opening June 1st at Six Flags Magic Mountain is designed to break the 100 mile-an-hour barrier for the first time. The ride, called Superman the Escape, propels you from a standstill to 100 mile-an-hour in seven seconds up a four-hundred-foot tower, where you float in zero gravity until you drop backward.    Thats also at one-hundred miles an hour.  You are weightless for about 6 seconds, another record.
<P>But thats not all.  Competition is pushing designers to make rides faster and higher.
<P>Paul Ruben of the trade magazine Park World says "Were in the roller coaster arms race."   He should know.  His job has involved riding 400 roller coasters.  He says "Ive seen this occurring for 20 years or more. Every park likes to have bragging rights to the fastest, wildest ride for at least one year."
<P>Las Vegas makes its bid with two rides called The Big Shot and The High Roller, both on top of a new one-thousand foot tower. The High Roller tools around a track near the top. The Big Shot shoots you up toward the top then drops you back.  Said one man,    "This is the most exciting thing Ive ever done next to jumping out of an airplane," (which I wouldnt do either.)
<P>Superman and Big Shot use "Star Wars" technology - electromagnetic motors developed for the military.  The motorswhite boxes along the trackspull magnets on the cars, shooting you faster as you cross each one.    Scientists experimented with them to shoot satellites into orbit on tracks. On Superman, YOU are the payload.
<P>Electromagnetic propulsion has already replaced chains and motors on rides in Mexico City, Kentucky and Wisconsin. Other such rides are opening at Worlds of Fun in Kansas City, Mo.; Universal Studios Florida; and Dreamland, near Sydney, Australia.  
<P>Promoters in the amusement business have been bragging about hundred mile-an-hour roller coasters since the 1920s. But that was before radar guns and truth-in-advertising laws.    Actually, 82 mph is the record right now, claimed jointly by Desperado at Buffalo Bills Casino in Stateline, Nev., and the Steel Phantom in Kennywood, outside Pittsburgh.    
<P>Whats it going to be like to ride Superman the Escape?  Rumor has it that Paul Weyrich is going to be the FIRST rider, and hell give you a full report.<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
<center>
