<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 13, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Sacrificing Principle for Party Loyalty"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

<P>
How do I hate this town? Let me count the ways! For one thing, almost no one really puts himself on the line for what he says he believes in.<P>
Case in point. Majority Leader Dick Armey wears his conservatism on his sleeve. To hear him talk, you would think he is one of the most principled of men ever to grace the Leadership of either party. I am sure he thinks of himself as principled. But Dick Armey is a party man first and foremost. And as a party man he puts protecting incumbents ahead of principle.<P>
Congresswoman Sue Kelly is one such incumbent. She voted against many items in the "Contract with America." When the Leadership said last summer that the Labor HHS Appropriations Bill was Armageddon and twisted arms until they hurt with GOP members who were reluctant to vote for the bill, Sue Kelly defied the Leadership. Worst of all, Sue Kelly was one of five Republicans to vote with President Clinton against the partial birth abortion bill.<P>
Sue Kellys opponent in the GOP primary is former Congressman Joe DioGuardi. DioGuardi is famous for having been the candidate who retired Bella Abzug from the House of Representatives. DioGuardi, when he served in the House, was the only certified public accountant to ever to do so. It is DioGuardi who pointed to the irregularities of the House majority which Speaker Gingrich was pleased to pick up on when he took over a year and a half ago.<P>
DioGuardi would be a loyal soldier when it came to things such as the "Contract." He would never vote against the Leadership on a key appropriations bill. In New Yorks multi-party system, DioGuardi already has the Right to Life party line. He would not be a dissenter on an issue like partial birth abortions. Yet Dick Armey, to help protect Sue Kelly, has gone so far as to call potential DioGuardi contributors in New York to ask them not to give to the DioGuardi campaign. Other members of the Leadership have tried to make the case for Kelly as well on the grounds that the GOP will lose the seat if she is not the nominee.<P>
First of all, if DioGuardi wins the GOP nomination and already has the Conservative and Right to Life party nominations, he will have an excellent chance of getting elected. But even if Kelly had the better chance of holding the seat, is incumbent loyalty worth sacrificing ones principles? Is it worth helping someone who is so liberal that even partial birth abortion doesnt stir her conscience? Is incumbent loyalty worth stabbing a fine upstanding man like DioGuardi in the back?<P>
Take the case of Congressman Bill Goodling of Pennsylvania. Speaker Gingrich gives passionate speeches about how the labor unions are out to destroy his Republican majority. Indeed they are and first among them is the National Education Association, the teachers union. When push comes to shove, Congressman Goodling, a former teacher, does the NEAs biding inside the GOP caucus.<P>
Goodling, who was first elected to replace his father George Goodling in 1974, was challenged in the Republican primary by civic activist Charlie Gerow. Gerow ran because he wanted to join the likes of the eager young freshmen who have made such a difference in Congress. Goodlings cozy relationship with the NEA was one of the key issues in the campaign. Well, who made an all-embracing appearance in the district for Bill Goodling at the strategic moment when it was clear it was a horse race? Why Speaker Gingrich, of course. <P>
When the results were in, Goodling was only re-nominated with a 53% to 47% vote. Gerow contends that if Gingrich had just stayed out, he would have defeated Goodling in this heavily Republican district. Then the NEA would not have had a mole inside the GOP ranks. But incumbent loyalty is more important to the Leadership than principle, when principle means standing up for those who believe the same things that the Leadership professes to believe.<P>
Perhaps one can morally justify neutrality on the part of the Leadership in such cases.  After all, members of the Leadership are put in a difficult position when one of their members is challenged in a primary. But all out support for incumbent members who are challenged by candidates of principle is next to impossible to justify if you really believe in the causes you preach to the faithful on a daily basis. No wonder the American electorate has grown increasingly cynical.<P>
Contrast this incumbent loyalty among Republicans with the Democrats. Congressman Ralph Hall of Texas is perhaps the most conservative Democrat in Congress. His voting record is better than that of most Republicans. A couple of times since he was first elected in 1980, Hall was perceived to be in trouble. He might have been replaced with a Republican. The Democratic Leadership was nowhere to be found. Hall was on his own. That is because Hall routinely votes with the Republicans on issues and defies the Democratic Leadership even on crucial votes. Their loyalty to liberalism was greater than their loyalty to one of their incumbents who votes against them. Even though Hall is a close friend of mine and I am glad he survived those challenges, I have to admire the liberals for at least standing for something.<P>
One possible Republican exception to this sorry state of affairs is Oklahomas freshman Representative Steve Largent. Late last year Speaker Gingrich sought to punish a group of conservatives because they didnt cave in when he did on shutting down the government. Largent then stepped in and did the fund-raisers for those on whom Gingrich canceled out. It worked out well. The public would rather pay to see a star athlete like Largent any day over a Washington politician.<P>
What Largent did took real fortitude. But of course he is a freshman. Were he serving his ninth term like Gingrich or his sixth term like Armey, he might not be as eager to cross a member of the Leadership.<P>
There is a reason that many of us who used to be adamantly opposed to term limits are now among its most ardent backers. The longer I stay here and see good men like DioGuardi and Gerow stabbed in the back by supposed philosophical standard bearers such as Gingrich and Armey, the more passionate about term limits I become.<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
