<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 12, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Making a Tax Cut Better"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>
Last week, Wednesday, I was witness to a dialogue between a freshman Senator and a freshman Congressman. That conversation got to the essence of where this nation is going in fiscal terms.<P>
The Senator was John Ashcroft, the former Governor of Missouri. He was explaining his proposal to make social security taxes deductible. Such a tax cut would mean an average middle class family would save more than $1700 a year in federal taxes. The Ashcroft program would cost $35 billion for its first year and more than $50 billion each year thereafter.<P>
The Congressman was Wisconsins Mark Neumann, the single most focused Member of the House on the question of our national debt.<P>
Neumann asked how the Senator was going to "pay for this legislation in terms of spending cuts."  The Senator from Missouri was vague.  "Well cut some money from corporate welfare and well get some money through welfare reform and from overhead expenses from the federal government," Ashcroft told the Congressman.<P>
"No, I mean specifically," Neumann replied. "What exactly would you cut and how much?"<P>
The Senator didnt know. Neumann continued, "Look, I like tax cuts. I want to vote for this legislation. But I cant vote for anything which will enlarge the deficit. Unless you know exactly what you are going to cut and from where youre going to cut it, the bill will end up enlarging the deficit."<P>
The Senator was silent. Neumann was exactly right. <P>
I think the Ashcroft idea is a splendid one. It would provide a middle class tax cut in exactly the way it should be provided. I hope his bill gains traction. But the day has passed when any responsible legislator should propose any piece of legislation without giving specific consideration to what will be cut from federal spending if the legislation is passed. <P>
With trillions of dollars in off book debt and unfunded liabilities, not to mention the current budget deficit, we simply cannot afford to pass legislation without looking at the precise consequences of enacting such bills. We have been avoiding such consequences for the past several decades. Look where it has brought us.<P>
The correct answer to all this is that we should do both. We ought to pass Ashcrofts bill, but Ashcroft should spell out precisely what portions of the federal budget he will cut out in order to make up for the lost revenue his bill would engender. Then we will have the best of both worlds. We will be giving a tax cut to the people who need it most, in the most equitable method possible. At the same time we will further cut federal spending in other areas so as not to enlarge the debt. All responsible legislators need to ask the questions Mark Neumann asked. Then we will truly be making progress. <P>


<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
