<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 9, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Supporting Tyranny over Freedom"
</h2>
(Delivered by Brad Keena)
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

<P>
A 58-year-old, highly educated, and soft spoken freedom fighter is, as we speak, 
conducting a hunger strike in a Belarus jail. He is the victim of a Stalinist style 
crackdown which is taking place in the former Soviet Republic. 
<p>Yuri Khadykas crime is that he dared to speak out against the repressive and dictatorial 
regime of hard line Communist Alexandr Lukashenko. Lukashenko is trying to 
reintegrate his country with Russia without a vote of the people giving him authority to 
do so. Lukashenko admires Adolph Hitler and yearns for the return of a true Russian 
leader like Josef Stalin so that at least real order can be restored. 
<p>Among all of the former Soviet Republics, Belarus has made the least progress in moving 
toward democracy and free enterprise. Even in places such as Georgia, Armenia, and the 
Central Asian Republics things are better off than in Belarus. Lukashenko has suspended 
the parliament, even though his fellow Communists have a lopsided majority there. He 
does not want to give a forum to the few Democratic voices who serve in that body and 
that is where Yuri Khadyka comes in. 
<p>Freedom fighters are given no access to the media. Their voices in elected government 
have been silenced. The only alternative for them now is to take to the streets. But for 
doing so, Khadyka and a couple hundred organizers of a 30,000 person demonstration in 
downtown Minsk were arrested on April 26th. 
<p>Khadyka has not been allowed to talk to his lawyer. He may languish in jail for up to six 
months before there is any trial, if there is one. And in Lukashenkos Belarus, the 
outcome of the trial will be a forgone conclusion, just as the trials of dissidents were 
foreordained in the former Soviet Union. 
<p>What is happening in Belarus is symbolic of what is happening in other places in the 
East. It is the prototype for what will take place if Communist candidate Gannady 
Zuganov is elected President in the upcoming elections. He has promised a similar 
crackdown on those regarded as opponents of the Communist ideology.
<p>To us, Khadyka is not just some remote figure we hear about in short- wave radio 
coverage of foreign developments. He is someone we know well. Bob Krieble and I have 
had lengthy discussions with him on several occasions. His son, 29-year-old Alexey, has 
worked for us at the Krieble Institute of the Free Congress Foundation for the past four 
years. He is one of the young, dedicated freedom fighters who have risked their lives to 
help promote freedom and democracy in the former Soviet empire. 
<p>Last Saturday night I was awakened in the middle of the night with news of the ominous 
developments in Belarus. Alexey pleaded for our help to get word of the plight of the 
Belarus freedom fighters to American officials. Well, our discussions with the State 
Department were exactly what you would expect. This Administration, while willing to 
involve itself in imposing a leftist government in Haiti, is unwilling to lift a finger to 
protest repression in Belarus. 
<p>The realities of the repression there do not square with this nations policy of the 
reconstruction of the former Soviet Union. Yes, the State Department wants to see the 
former Soviet Union re-established in some new form. Our officials think that will bring 
stability to the region. Yes, it will bring stability the stability of the graveyard. 
<p>While most of the other organizers who have been arrested in Belarus have now been 
released from jail, Khadyka remains there. He is a special problem case because he is also 
a Christian leader who has sought the return of the ancient Bylorussian language as well. 
Someone with his views is not convenient for the Lukashenko regime. 
<p>We have managed to interest some Members of Congress in what is happening in 
Belarus. Robert Novak devoted todays syndicated column to this subject. Perhaps little 
by little we will bring world attention to the plight of freedom loving people in this small 
former Soviet Republic of l2 million people. 
<p>The issue here isnt that Yuri Khadyka is a truly fine man, which he is. The issue here 
that the United States government is cooperating with pro-Communist forces in the 
reconstruction of the Evil Empire. That is not why our men and women died on the 
battlefield opposing tyranny in this long and bloody twentieth Century. This is not why 
countless more unsung heroes died during the Cold War.
<p>The time to speak up against this evil is now before it is too late. Failure to do so may 
well mean that the next Century will bring confrontation with a new evil empire all over 
again. Only this time, the outcome might not be the same.


<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
