<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 7, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"House Speaker Cultivating Challengers"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>


<P>
These are not the best of times for Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich. First, he was savagely attacked by New York Senator Al D'Amato who claimed that Gingrich had misread the 1994 elections and thus had proposed radical initiatives instead of the incremental changes the voters wanted. Now comes word from inside the House that some Members are talking seriously about challenging Gingrich for the Speaker's post in the next Congress.<P>
The challenge comes not from the dozen or so hard-core conservatives among the freshmen who have never cared much for the Speaker. Rather, the challenge comes from an outer core of less-adamant conservatives. One multi-term Member told me he knew of at least two candidates who were considering the run. All of the current members of the leadership strongly back Gingrich and are opposed to any run against him.<P>
This whole issue is relevant only if Republicans keep control of the Congress, because in the event they become a minority, the Republicans will lose one leadership position and Gingrich has already said publicly that he would drop out in such a case.<P>
The rap against the Speaker from those who want an alternative is two-fold. First, his opponents claim, he plays games on crucial issues. There is now a dispute, for example, between the Speaker and Majority Leader Dick Armey over the minimum wage issue. Armey says he doesn't want to vote on the issue at all because the minimum wage is part of the Democratic agenda. Gingrich points to a letter he received from 38 "moderate" Republican Members of the House who back the Minimum wage.  He says a vote on the issue is inevitable and so he wants it brought to the floor with Republican provisions attached. <P>Conservative opponents of Gingrich claim that he actually encouraged the "moderates" to write the letter to him in the first place. They quote one of their colleagues as telling them "I didn't want to sign the letter (on the minimum wage) but Newt asked me to." Their claim is that this is all too typical of how Gingrich operates, pitting one side against another. Moreover they contend that when liberal Republicans bolt the party line, nothing is said to them at all. But when conservatives disagree with Gingrich they are taken to the woodshed, cursed at, and told to get in the real world.<P>
The second rap against Gingrich is that he is often unfocused and flits from issue to issue. The Gingrich opponents claim that the Speaker all but abrogated his responsibilities earlier this year, telling the other House leaders they were going to run the show while he concentrated on strategies to get Bob Dole elected President and to raise money for the Republican party.<P>
Opponents think they have a chance to defeat Gingrich because of the dissatisfaction among the current freshman class as well as the fact that a number of older Members were never fond of the one-time fire brand in the first place.  In addition, they believe, incoming freshmen won't have the kind of attachment to the Speaker that this class once had.<P>
As I see it, the challenge to Gingrich, when all is said and done, probably won't work. I think his adversaries ought to step back and look at the situation and then take some action.<P>
First off, they should acknowledge that Gingrich is without peer in proclaiming a vision for their party. It is a party which otherwise lacks vision.  They should be reluctant to toss overboard the one person they have in their midst who has that capability.<P>
Second, they should call the Speaker's bluff when they think he is playing games with them. Newt is, above all, a realist. If he knows he can't get by with the sort of tactics which enrage his opponents he won't try them. The next time they get "woodsheded" for doing the right thing, they should go public with the issue. In such cases, the vast majority of ordinary folks will be with Members trying to do the right thing, not with the Speaker. This is part of Newt's style. Last year, for example, a delegation from Focus on the Family visited the Speaker expressing extreme discomfort at the direction of the Republican party. Gingrich told the delegation if he were in their position, he would threaten a third party. This is exactly the way Gingrich operates.  If things like that become a public issue, the Speaker is not likely to continue down the same path.<P>
Finally, these conservatives should look for someone among their ranks to fill the shoes of Vin Weber and Bob Walker. When Newt Gingrich first came to the Congress back in 1978, he was extremely unfocused.  As a result, he was not taken seriously by his colleagues. Mr. Weber, a former six-term Congressman from Minnesota, recognized great potential in Gingrich. So did Rep. Walker (R-PA), the watchdog of the House floor. Together, they gently but firmly took Newt's hand and helped to organize and focus him. They were an integral part of his success. But Mr. Weber left the Congress in 1992.  Rep. Walker is leaving at the end of this term. Both need to be replaced. Speaker Gingrich came to trust them and rely on them even though initially they were not the best of friends. I would suggest that conservatives disgruntled with the Speaker try to become to Gingrich the kind of assets that Weber and Walker were.  This would afford them the type of positive influence over the Speaker that these two Members had.<P>
Most challenges to Republican leadership figures turn out to be just talk. This challenge, although being discussed by serious Members of the House, will likely also turn out to be just talk.  That is, unless of course, the Speaker himself performs in such a way that he drives Members into the arms of his opponents.<P>



<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
