</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 2, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Mayor Should Heed Friends Advice"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>


<P>
It is an American tradition that local politics is always more colorful than national politics. So ordinarily the strange wanderings of a Mayor would not be suitable for a commentary with a national focus. But when it comes to the Mayor of the nation's capital, it is another matter. <P>
Marion Barry is a national, indeed, international figure. So when the Mayor suddenly leaves town for a retreat in St. Louis to reconnect with God and his spirituality, it is news. It is news, even more so, because one of Mayor Barry's closest friends, Rock Newman, who headed up the "Rock The Vote" effort for Barry to return to office in 1994, has now called on the Mayor to resign. The Mayor isn't denying that this is a consideration.<P>
Now, Marion Barry is still recovering from prostate cancer. He has had alcohol and drug problems in the past. He served six months in jail for a charge related to the use of cocaine. His subsequent election as alderman and then comeback as Mayor was called the political miracle of the century.<P>
I am not trying to pile on here. But it was Marion Barry's aides who called the news media in the middle of the night to tell them to show up at the Baltimore airport at 6:30 a.m. Wednesday for a Barry press conference.  The press arrived only to have the Mayor tell the reporters that they should leave him and his wife alone. He was headed to St. Louis to a retreat house. On the surface it is very confusing; but since just about everyone else in this town is offering an opinion about what is happening to the Mayor, I shall offer one of my own.<P>
For decades now, Marion Barry's faith has been in government. Even as a young radical agitator he was always trying to get the government to spend more on his people. He upset the city's establishment in getting elected Mayor. When he did so, he greatly expanded the city government. Marion Barry became a hero to many because he was able to put them on the payroll. His liberal friends in the Congress blessed him with every sort of experimental federal program imaginable. They gave Barry control over billions of federal dollars with which to put more people on the payroll. None of these programs was ever monitored very closely.<P>
Washington, DC, was the laboratory of liberalism. If you needed help, the Mayor had a taxpayer-supported program for you. It worked for a time. But as is the case with all solutions which are not based in reality, the fix was not permanent.<P>
Marion Barry knew the heights of power. While in prison he knew the depths of powerlessness. He vowed he would come back and indeed, five years after he was released from jail, he was back at City Hall. But what the Washington, DC, Mayor came back to was not the same place he left. The consequences of his liberal programs had come back to haunt the city. The population was down. Crime was up. The deficit was high. Private sector jobs were low. New federal programs were out. Federal control over Barry's budget was in.<P>
The politics Marion Barry had practiced so well over so many years had ground to a halt. The Mayor, who was used to solving a problem by giving someone a taxpayer supported job no matter what their skills or productivity, was now virtually powerless to act. He was presiding over a city with sharply increasing problems; a city which no longer could be run by the whims of its Mayor. It was run by tough regulators determined to bring spending under control.<P>
Marion Barry's total faith in government had brought him to this dead end. That is the making of a spiritual crisis. At such times, even people who have disregarded most of what the Bible teaches will turn to the Scriptures. I believe that what is causing at least some of the Mayor's problems is the realization that he has placed his faith in the wrong place. Bigger government did not bring salvation.<P>
Facing the ruins of what once was a well-ordered city, Marion Barry cannot come to grips with reality. Even after the Republicans took over the Congress and made it clear the city was going to have to shape up, Barry went on acting as if nothing had happened. Committee Chairmen and even the minority Democrats on Capitol Hill accused the Mayor of engaging in fantasy. He did not want to believe that the way things had been for decades was now at an end.<P>
The Mayor has come face to face with the real world and he doesn't like what he sees. It doesn't conform to the untruths he has sold himself and his followers. The world as it really exists, which Mayor Barry now confronts on a daily basis, is really an unpleasant place. The instant gratification solutions Barry has applied  all these years are no longer available. 
<P>I wish the Mayor well in reconnecting with God. I hope this time it is the true God and not the gods of liberalism who have been enshrined in Washington these many years. Meanwhile the Mayor would be well to heed the advice of  Rock Newman. The nation's capital could use new leadership that has the ability to cope with the new realities.<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
