<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 1, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Republicans Should Stick to the Issues" 
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>
There is no doubt that Bill Clinton is on a roll. His latest poll numbers show him with an unprecedented 21-point lead over presumed Republican nominee Bob Dole. That poll doesnt even take into account what will happen if, as is likely, Ross Perot runs again and splits the anti-Clinton vote.
<P>All of the dire predictions which many of us made about Clintons foreign policy adventures, especially our involvement in Bosnia, have thus far not come true. For a President who said that domestic issues would be his primary focus, Clinton seems to be making quite a name for himself in the Balkans, in the Middle East, in Russia and  elsewhere.
<P>And while the economy isnt exactly bustling along, growth is probably just adequate enough to prevent electoral problems for the President.
<P>Then there is Whitewater and associated problems. Whitewater was supposed to draw Clinton a primary opponent. It did not. He is the first Democrat since FDR not to have one. he President just made a three-and-a-half-hour videotaped interview for the criminal trial of James and Susan McDougal and Governor Jim Guy Tucker of Arkansas. They are the three charged with conspiracy and fraud in the Whitewater affair. The text of the tape will be released but not the tape itself because the White House believes that Clinton opponents would try to turn the tape into a 60-second commercial.
<P>Whitewater has been in the news since before Clinton took office and yet it has failed to effect the standing of this President. My co-hosts and I debated this on last nights Campaign 96 show with Mark Levine of Landmark Legal Foundation. Levine believes that Clinton is in for big-time trouble down the road on Whitewater. I disagree. I think if, as is probable, Gov. Tucker gets acquitted, Whitewater will be over and done with. To pursue it after such a verdict will simply appear too partisan. Republicans would run the risk of a significant backlash.
<P>The polls show that a majority of the people in the United States believe that the Clintons are hiding something. But the same polls show that the majority doesnt care. The question is why dont they care? Well, first off Whitewater is too complicated to understand. The public will not be interested in this case unless and until there is something simple which they can relate to. They understood Hillary and the cattle futures issue. They understood the Watergate break-in. They understood Chairman Rostenkowskis misdeeds. They dont understand this case. Secondly, whatever the Clintons did, it mostly took place before he was President. True, Vice President Spiro Agnew was driven from office by what he did as Governor of Maryland. But most voters want to know what Clinton has done while President, not something which happened a decade and a half ago. Thirdly, the voters today are cynical about politicians. There is no shock value to the notion that a politician and his wife might be in this game to get something for themselves. In fact the public believes that all politicians are similarly guilty.  Since it is presumed, guilt that is confirmed just doesnt have that much of an impact.<P>
Yes, of course, there is the media which made a national cause out of John Sununu getting dental work while on official business. But the media has not covered Whitewater with any intensity. Still, I cant fault the national media on this one as I have done on many other issues. After Clinton came into office, hundreds of Pulitzer Prize seeking reporters swarmed into Little Rock seeking to break the story that would bring this President down. They did that, not because they disliked Clinton, (most of them voted for him) but because it would bring them more power. Some journalists really worked at it for months going on years, and with unlimited expense accounts. They simply never found the smoking gun.
<P>Looking at Clintons standing with the voters, some Republicans are hoping against hope that Whitewater will turn into something to rescue their fortunes. They are foolish to count on it. If it comes at all, it could well be after this President is re-elected.
<P>I have said from the beginning of this case that I didnt think it would impact politically. Republicans, I suggested, would be well off to make the philosophical case against liberalism and the Clinton Presidency. If something does come of Whitewater they will get an added benefit but meanwhile the 1996 election would be about real issues which matter to the American people. They have not done so. And now they are reduced to hoping that one of Clintons friends will drop something sensational at the Whitewater hearings or that somehow the jury in Arkansas will find Governor Tucker guilty. Thus the reality is that Bob Dole cannot win the Presidency. Only Bill Clinton can lose it. That has never been a winning strategy to gain power in this country. Even if the Republicans do take power under these circumstances, they do so without any mandate to change anything.
<P>It is the ninth-hour and the sun is nearly setting on this election season. It is still not too late for this election to be about opposing philosophies and clear differences on issues. If that case is made, Whitewater wont be needed. If something substantive relating to Whitewater does break between now and the election, it will only underscore the philosophical case which has already been made. It remains to be seen now if, at least, conservatives will stick to the issues this year instead of waiting for the political equivalent of the lottery known as Whitewater.<P>

<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
