<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
April 25, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
The Independent Council
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

When Independent Counsel Lawrence Walsh was busy harassing witnesses over Iran-Contra during the Reagan Administration, Democrats cheered. As Independent Counsel Ken Starr conducts his Whitewater trial in Little Rock, Republicans cheer.<P>
What of the ordinary Americans who are not part of the established political parties? Well, in my opinion, they have little to cheer about when it comes to the way the Independent Counsel system functions. It is a system out of control.<P>
In reality, Independent Counsels are accountable to no one. Lawrence Walsh spent $40 million of taxpayers money, obligating his victims to spend millions of their own money defending themselves. For this he got a couple of forced convictions which probably would not have taken place had Walsh's targets not panicked and agreed to plead guilty. The Independent Counsel, investigating former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, went so far afield in his investigation that he even drew a rebuke from the federal judges who appointed him. <P>
I know that Republican partisans are hoping against hope that Independent Counsel Starr will get convictions in Arkansas. However, there is every indication that Governor Tucker, at least, will be found not guilty and that the Starr investigation may collapse thereafter. Meantime, Democratic Senators Harry Reid of Nevada and John Breaux of Louisiana have called on Starr to resign because of alleged conflicts of interest in his private law practice. Among the charges that these Senators and others make is that Starr represented the Bradley Foundation in a Milwaukee school choice case and the Bradley foundation has provided funds for, among other entities, NET. NET, after all, doesn't approve of much of what the Clinton Administration has done. What many think about the work of Independent Counsels depends upon whose ox is being gored.<P>
Against this background, Congressman Jay Dickey, a Democrat turned Republican from Arkansas, has introduced legislation which would require that after two years the Independent Counsel would be subject to the usual oversight process of the Congress. Such counsels would have to come to the Appropriations Committees to seek a renewal of their funding. Moreover, the Dickey legislation would require that Independent Counsels drop outside legal work while serving in that capacity.  This would prevent accusations of conflict of interest.<P>
Dickey's bill is getting a lot of favorable coverage in Arkansas because it is seen as a slap at Ken Starr. But, in fact, Dickey has made it clear that he has high regard for Starr and does not think the charges of conflict of interest against him are meritorious. Dickey is moving on a principle here. He believes, as do I, that no one should be above our system of checks and balances.
<P>Right now Independent Counsels have a blank check to spend as much as they want for as long as they wish. Their mandate is limitless so they often conduct fishing expeditions at the taxpayers expense. Those of us who believe in a rule of law know very well that our Founding Fathers would have a collective heart attack if they saw this system in operation. 
<P>Dickey's bill should be approved by this Republican Congress. The Democrats would have to vote for it. Senate Democrats certainly could not filibuster the legislation after what they have said about Ken Starr. President Clinton, thinking he will be re-elected, will eagerly sign the legislation.
Regardless of who is in power, this bill is necessary because it will end the highly dubious status of these Independent Counsels who have no accountability.
<P>Two years is enough time to pursue a valid investigation if there is substance to charges being made. In that case, an Independent Counsel will have no problem justifying his work and even a partisan Congress, under pressure from the media, will have to continue an appropriate level of funding. 
This legislation restores some badly needed balance to the system.
<P>The problem here is that some in the Republican Leadership rather enjoy seeing President Clinton and his associates twisting in the wind. They have forgotten what it was like to have Lawrence Walsh on his rampage. Now they've gotten their pay-back at the expense of Bill Clinton. But a pay-back in reverse may be coming with a vengeance if Bob Dole gets to be President. 
<P>No partisan advantage is worth the distortion to our constitutional system which the Independent Counsel system represents. This Congress should immediately pass the Dickey initiative. In fact, Dickey's bill doesn't go far enough for me. The whole system should be repealed. But since the votes aren't there to accomplish that, at least the Dickey bill is a step in the right direction. If the Republican leaders have any sense of integrity they will act on the Dickey measure forthwith. 
<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
