<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
April 22, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Earth Day' its Own Religion"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>
Thirty-two years ago today, two momentous things happened. Our first
daughter, Dawn Ceol, was born and the first "Earth Day" was proclaimed.
There is no connection between the two, I can assure you, although Dawn has
shown a lot of interest in gardening of late. <P>
It is true enough that we human beings have been given custody of earth and
that we should take appropriate care of what has been entrusted to us. 
But it is also true that in the Book of Genesis, it is clear that man was
given dominion over the earth. There was not a word from God suggesting that
we should preserve everything just as it was created. Quite the contrary,
God gave man an intellect and the ability to develop the earth.<P> 
Rather than a call for us to be responsible, as we continue to make progress
in unlocking what God knows anyway, "Earth Day" has become an ideology or a
substitute religion. The underlying assumption behind this ideology is that
the earth was created in a pristine state and it is man who is the problem.
If only we didn't spoil the earth with our use of resources, then we could
live in the beauty of nature again.<P> 
No one defends the real polluters. No one suggests that all businesses or
individuals have been completely responsible or even efficient in the use of
natural resources. But the idea that we are the problem is a direct denial
of God's word in Genesis. And that is the heart of the conflict over "Earth
Day." <P>
While not all who celebrate this occasion have adopted that philosophy,
those who have created the occasion have a neo-Pantheism at the heart of
what they believe. They worship not the God of creation, but nature itself.
These views are hardly new. We have evidence of similar ideas going back to
ancient times. Since nature is to be elevated, and man is to be subject to
nature, of course private property becomes an outmoded concept.<P> 
Nature, so many of the "Earth Day" advocates believe, cannot be confined to
a single individual but belongs to us all. Private property flies in the
face of this ideology. So behind the niceties of celebrating the beauties of
the natural state of the earth is an attack on the individual and his
rights. Thus it is fair to say that most so-called "Greens" are only green
on the outside. At the core they are red or at least pink.<P> 
When all is said and done there is little difference between what the
radical elements of the "Earth Day" movement believe and what the Marxists
teach. I say teach, because if you have ever visited a Communist nation you
will note that the reality is in stark contrast to Marxist beliefs. This is
especially true about the environment. At all of the international meetings,
the Communists were always pushing the Green agenda. Yet they left their own
nations in environmental ruins. <P>
So on this "Earth Day," while mindful of the importance of taking good care
of what has been entrusted to us temporarily, I prefer to celebrate Dawn's
birthday instead. She has been an outstanding example of what it means to
develop one's God given talents. I'd rather trust Dawn and her good husband
Ed to do good things with the property they own, then to put my trust in an
ideology which defies not only the Scriptures but reality as well. So Happy
Birthday, Dawn. Now get busy in your garden.
<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
<center>
<P>
