<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
April 19th, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Another Off-Book Mistake"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>


Congressman Bud Shuster (R-Pennsylvania) led a successful effort in the House of Representatives to pass his Truth-in-Budgeting bill by a vote of 284-143. The Shuster measure takes the Transportation Trust Fund out of the budget. This presumably would release more of the money collected through transportation taxes to be spent on local roads and other projects. On the surface that seems fair enough. People pay taxes on gasoline and airline tickets and the money should be spent for projects relating to their taxation.
<P>
The problem is that the transportation trust funds are used to offset other spending in the federal budget. So, in effect, this move means that another $30 billion will have to be cut from discretionary domestic spending to balance the budget if the Shuster measure should become law. That is why Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich (R-Ohio) and Appropriations Committee Chairman Bob Livingston (R-Louisiana) strongly opposed the bill. "We will never eliminate the deficit if we give some programs exalted, protected status," Livingston said.
Another opponent, Rep. Chris Shays (R-Connecticut) said, "While some call it the Truth-in-Budgeting Act, I would call it the Unbalanced Budget Act of 1996 or frankly the Pork Barrel Bill of 1996."
<P>
Shays and Livingston are correct. Even this strongly conservative House of Representatives couldn't bring itself to eliminate the Legal Services Corporation, the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, or the National Endowment for the Arts. That being the case, who is going to seriously suggest that this Congress or a subsequent Congress is going to come up with another $30 billion in domestic budget cuts to balance the budget?
<P>
This is just another attempt to hide spending off-book. As Harrison Fox of Citizens for Budget reform has pointed out, the off-book obligations of the federal government are greater than those of the federal budget and in many cases more dangerous because they are hidden from the public. I have complained about the Senate stopping most of the reforms which the House has passed in this Congress. Well, this is one time I hope the Senate doesn't go along with what the House has passed. 

<P>
In theory, Congressman Shuster is right. In practice, this measure would be a disaster and would move us that much further away from ever bringing our budget into balance.
<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
<center>
