</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>America's Tax System - Issues 96 - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 2</h3>
<center><h2> AMERICA'S TAX SYSTEM </H2>


<CITE><B>By <a href="/heritage/staff/mitchell.htm">Daniel J. Mitchell</a></B></CITE>
<P><A HREF="chpt2.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt2.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt2.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt2.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A> | <A HREF="chpt2.html#SELECTED">Selected Heritage Foundation Studies</A>  
| <a href="chpt2.html#EXP">Experts</a></P>
</center>
<a href="tax_1.gif">Chart 1</a>: Rich Pay Greater Share After Reagan Cuts<br>
<a href="tax_2.gif">Chart 2</a>: Taxes Take Bigger Share of Family Budgets<br>
<a href="tax_3.gif">Chart 3</a>: Reagan Years Help All Income Classes<br>
<a href="tax_4.gif">Chart 4</a>: Federal Taxes Cost Average Family $10,084 a Year<br>
<a href="tax_ss.gif">Chart 5a</a>: Steady Increase in the Social Security Tax<br>
<a href="tax_5.gif">Chart 5</a>: Increase in Income Subject to Social Security Tax<br>
<a href="tax_6.gif">Chart 6</a>: Maximum Amount of Social Security Tax<br>
<a href="tax_7.gif">Chart 7</a>: Tax Revenues Grew During 1980s<br>
<a href="tax_8.gif">Chart 8</a>: Lower Tax Rates Work<br>
<a href="tax_9.gif">Chart 9</a>: Did Tax Cuts Cause the Deficit?<br>
<a href="tax_11.gif">Chart 11</a>: Reagan Deficit Performance Outshines Bush, Clinton<br>
<a href="tax_12.gif">Chart 12</a>: Tax Forms on a Postcard<br>
<a href="tax_13.gif">Chart 13</a>: No Tax on Poor Under Flat Tax<br>
<a href="tax_14.gif">Chart 14</a>: Tax Deduction and Home Values: No Relationship<br>
<a href="tax_15.gif">Chart 15</a>: Charitable Giving Closely Tied to Income Growth<br> 

<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>America's tax system is a disgrace. It severely penalizes  productive
economic behavior, especially by savers and investors  whose capital income is
subjected to as many as four layers of taxation.  It is so bewildering that
complying with its increasingly  complex forms, regulations, and other documents
consumes billions  of hours each year. And it imposes staggering economic damage
 reducing economic output by hundreds of billions of dollars  each year. The
real cost, however, is measured in lost jobs,  foregone income, lower living
standards, and reduced economic security.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>But lost prosperity is only part of the story. For many  Americans the most
reprehensible aspect of the current system is the way  it allows special
interests to manipulate the tax code for their  own advantage. Lobbyists with
enough money and access tilt the  playing field, creating special preferences
for the politically  well-connected. With the tax burden at record levels, many
taxpayers  understandably want to protect their earnings, but today's system  of
loopholes, credits, exemptions, and deductions fosters a  pervasive sense of
unfairness and encourages lawmakers to impose  even higher tax rates on income
which does not enjoy special status.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The best way to solve America's tax problem is to adopt a flat  tax. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->  No tax system is good for the
economy, but a flat tax would  allow significantly stronger economic growth by
replacing the  current tax code with a low rate, simple tax that removes the
bias  against savings and investment. Perhaps equally important, it would 
restore integrity to a tax system that has become synonymous  with
special-interest corruption. Under the flat tax, every taxpayer  plays by the
same rules. The multitude of forms required by today's  arcane tax law are
replaced by two simple postcards, one for  individuals' labor income and the
other for business and capital  income. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1995, the new Congress took a significant step in the right  direction by
delivering on its promise to pass badly needed  family tax relief to spur
economic growth. Taxpayers were  disappointed, however, when  just two years
after signing the largest tax  hike in U.S. history  President Clinton vetoed
the Balanced  Budget Act of 1995, which included about $220 billion in tax
relief over  a seven-year period. This relatively small package  which  amounts
to returning to the taxpayer just 2 cents of every dollar from  the $11.5
trillion in tax revenues the government expects to  collect over the next seven
years  included a $500-per-child tax credit,  a reduction in the capital gains
tax, and a modest expansion of  Individual Retirement Accounts. This legislation
marked the first  time since 1981 that Congress had voted to ease the tax
burden, but  it still did not come close to offsetting the negative impact of 
tax increases imposed by Presidents George Bush and Bill Clinton  in 1990 and
1993; the 1995 tax cut was less than one-third the  combined size of these two
tax increases.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P> 
<P>As important as Congress's proposed tax cuts were to  taxpayers 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->  and economic growth, they amounted
to using a Band-Aid  when what the situation really required was radical
surgery.  Serious, fundamental reform must be based on a recognition of two 
essential realities: Excessive taxation harms the economy, and the  liberal
notion that any problem can be solved by taxing the rich  is self-defeating.
Higher tax rates simply encourage wealthy  taxpayers, who already are
over-taxed, to hide, shelter, underreport,  and reduce their income. A much
better way to get the rich to  pay more, and one that will help lower - and
middle-income  workers by boosting savings and investment, is to cut tax rates.
The  attached <a href="tax_1.gif">chart</a> illustrates how lower tax rates in the 1980s  dramatically
increased the percentage of the income tax burden borne  by the rich. Even more
important, however, these reductions  triggered the longest peacetime economic
expansion in U.S. history and  led to the creation of 21 million new jobs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The problems of the tax code are almost too numerous to 
quantify. For example: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The tax burden on families is at a record high.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>- </CITE></B>    Capital gains taxes depress investment and
prevent capital  from being used in ways that maximize growth. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     High marginal tax rates depress work effort and
undermine  job creation. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The alternative minimum tax imposes huge
compliance costs  and drains resources from American industry. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The estate tax is so onerous that many of the
nation's most  productive citizens are driven into early retirement, and some
even  flee the country. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>- </CITE></B>    Double taxation of savings depresses our ability
to generate  new capital. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Double taxation of corporate income reduces
business  investment and biases companies to take on extra debt. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The conclusion is obvious: The tax system today is so  fundamentally flawed
that the only realistic solution is to scrap it and  begin again.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>These flaws in the current tax code can be communicated by  emphasizing
three main themes:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>1. Excessive tax rates.</B> The federal income tax has a top rate  of
39.6 percent. This means that successful entrepreneurs and  others with high
incomes receive barely 60 cents of benefit for every  dollar they contribute to
the nation's economy. The result is less  incentive to engage in productive
behavior, which leads in turn  to lower levels of work, saving, investment,
risk-taking, and  entrepreneurship. Added to this are state and local taxes,
which can  increase the total burden by as much as 11 percent, and the  Medicare
payroll tax, which adds another 2.9 percent. Moreover, while  those with lower
incomes may seem to be penalized less, usually  facing income tax rates of 15
percent and 28 percent, they also are  subjected to the full 15.3 percent
payroll tax, <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#1">1</A></B></TT> in
addition to state  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  local taxes. In other words,
almost all taxpayers are paying  about 40 percent of each additional dollar of
income they earn to  the government.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>According to the Tax Foundation, the average taxpayer in  1995 worked until
May 6 to satisfy the revenue demands of  federal, state, and local government.
This number could have dropped by  a day or two in 1996 if the President had
signed the legislation  approved by Congress in 1995. Nevertheless, the cost of
the tax  system remains the largest item in the average family's budget, 
exceeding the combined cost of food, clothing, shelter, and  transportation. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2. Complexity.</B> Americans spend too much time deciphering  IRS forms,
regulations, and rulings. Several years ago, an  IRS-commissioned study
estimated that taxpayers spend 5.4 billion hours  on their federal tax returns 
more than all the man-hours used in  the entire automotive industry in America.
According to the  Tax Foundation, our tax system imposes $192 billion in 
compliance costs on the economy: not money sent to Washington, not  foregone
economic growth, but the cost of the lawyers,  accountants, lobbyists, tax
preparers, and man-hours needed to comply with  the current tax code. Of this
amount, three-quarters is due to the  federal income tax alone.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>3. Bias against savings and investment.</B> The current system 
discourages Americans from saving and investing. Perhaps the  most pernicious
feature of the tax code is the way it subjects capital  income to discriminatory
treatment. If a taxpayer earns a dollar,  he can choose (after paying tax on the
money) to consume that  income or use it for savings and investment. If he
consumes the  dol
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 -->  lar, he will pay very little, if
any, additional federal tax. If  he chooses to invest his earnings, he is
treated like a criminal.  Depending on the type of investment, the government
may  subject any returns to as many as four additional layers of tax; needless 
to say, however, it does not share in any losses if the investment  does not
perform as expected. Not only is this policy unfair, but it  has profoundly
adverse consequences for the economy since all  economic theories agree that the
only way to generate higher  wages and rising living standards is through
savings and investment.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>How Taxes Slow the Economy and Cost Jobs </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The biggest long-term problem with the tax system is its impact  on income
and productivity. Although much has been made of a  supposed decline in
middle-class incomes over the last 20 years,  all income groups have seen their
incomes rise over time.  However, our current tax system has made this increase
smaller than it  could have been.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There is almost universal agreement among economists   even Marxists  that
incomes depend on productivity. Workers are  paid on the basis of what they
produce. Put another way, for incomes  to rise, productivity must increase, but
productivity increases  are closely linked to savings and to investment in
capital and  labor. Thus, the ability of workers to produce more is a function
of  increases in the quantity and quality of the machinery, tools,  equipment,
and technology with which they work. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The only systematic way to increase living standards and  income over time
is through more savings and investment in capital  and labor; in other words, in
the language of economics,  increased 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 -->  capital formation boosts the
productivity of labor. Capital and  labor are what economists call complementary
goods, because  the value of each increases when they are linked together. A 
citizen who invests money in a pension fund will get a good return on  that
money if it is put to work producing goods. Labor, conversely,  will receive
higher wages as a result of the new investment made  possible by those
retirement savings.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>This link between labor and capital explains why farmers  in America earn
more than farmers in Bangladesh. American  farmers do not work harder. They are
not smarter. They earn more  because they produce more, and they produce more
because they work  with sophisticated machinery, equipment, tools, technology,
and  production processes. This is also why factory workers in  America,
Germany, and Japan earn more than factory workers in  Brazil, Nigeria, and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfortunately, our tax code imposes particularly harsh penalties  on
so-called capital income. Consider, for example, a family that  decides to
sacrifice by setting aside 10 percent of its income in  order to build up a
retirement nest egg. It invests the money in a  new company, exposing itself to
the possible loss of all its savings.  One would assume the government would
want to reward this type  of entrepreneurial decision, but just the opposite is
the case. If  the family's investment turns out to be a wise one, the 
government imposes at least three, and sometimes four, levels of tax. First, 
any income of the new company is subject to the corporate income  tax; second,
when the money is paid out as a dividend to the  shareholder, the income is
subject to the personal income tax; third,  if the family ever decides to sell
its stock, it must pay a tax on  capital gains; and fourth, if this family
invested very wisely and  helped 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 -->  create tomorrow's Microsoft, the
government will tax the value  of its assets through the estate tax as its
members die. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As bad as all this sounds, it gets even worse. Policies such as  the
alternative minimum tax and depreciation often force  businesses and individuals
to overstate their income, making the real tax  rate even higher than the
statutory top rate. Our hypothetical  family could try to avoid some of these
taxes by simply putting money  in the bank, but even this has high costs. First,
the rate of return  on their savings will be lower because excessive taxes lower
the  demand for credit. Second, the government double taxes  savings. With the
exception of strictly limited IRAs and a handful of  other savings plans like
401(k)s, the money put into savings accounts  is taxed when it is deposited and
taxed on any interest it earns.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Needless to say, this pernicious anti-savings, anti-investment  bias in the
tax code sharply reduces the level of capital  formation. Many taxpayers look at
how the government punishes  success, decide that the financial sacrifice is not
worth it, and  consume their income rather than save and invest it. Ironically,
many  of these tax policies are designed to punish the &quot;rich,&quot; since 
they naturally have more money available for savings and  investment. The main
effect, however, is to reduce the wages and salaries  of people with lower and
middle incomes. Most wealthy people  can use tax shelters like municipal bonds
or hide their money  offshore to avoid taxes targeted at the so-called rich.
What these taxes  really do is discourage those on the lower rungs of the 
economic ladder from trying to become rich.
</P>
<P>
</P> 
<P>By contrast, the tax cuts of the 1980s show what happens if  tax 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  policy reduces the burden on
working, saving, and investing.  Once the economy received an unambiguous tax
cut, everything  President Reagan said would happen if tax rates were reduced
began  to happen. The economy began its longest period of growth in  peacetime
history. Incomes began to rise, with the increase benefiting  all groups  rich,
middle-class, and lower-income (see <a href="tax_3.gif">chart</a>). And,  of course, the miraculous job
creation machine began: 21 million  new jobs were created during the Reagan
boom.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>How Washington has Hiked Taxes on  Children  </B><TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#2">2</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Federal taxation of families with children has increased  dramatically over
the past four decades. In 1948, the typical family of  four paid just 3 percent
of its income to the federal government in  direct taxes. In 1994, the
equivalent family paid 24.5 percent of  its income to the federal government. As
the <a href="tax_2.gif">chart</a> below  shows, when state and local and indirect federal taxes are
included, the  tax burden on that family equals 37.6 percent of its income.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Federal income taxes have risen much faster for families with  children than
for other groups of Americans in the last four  decades. The root cause of this
growing anti-family bias is the  eroding value of the personal exemption. The
personal exemption for  children was intended to offset part of the annual cost
of raising  a child by allowing families to deduct an amount of money  from
their taxable income. In 1948, the personal exemption was  $600. This was equal
to roughly 17 percent of the median income of  a family of four (then $3,468)
and shielded 68 percent of  that family's income from federal income tax.
Families could  protect most of the remaining 32 percent by itemizing deductions
or  by taking the standard deduction. The result: In the late 1940s  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 -->  early 1950s, the average family
with children paid little or no  income tax.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In the past four decades, however, increases in the personal  exemption have
lagged far behind the rise in incomes and  inflation. As the value of the
personal exemption has declined, the  income tax paid by families with children
has increased. For the  personal exemption today to have the same value relative
to family  income that it had in 1948, it would have to have risen to $7,000 in 
1992, and to $8,000 in 1996. Instead, it is worth only $2,250 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The second blow to family finances has been the increase in  Social Security
taxes, technically known as &quot;payroll taxes.&quot;  In  1948, workers paid a
2 percent Social Security tax on annual wages of  up to $3,000; 1 percent was
paid directly by the employee and 1  percent indirectly by the employer through
the so-called  employer share.<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#3">3</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>By 1995, combined Social Security taxes have risen to 15.3  percent of wages
(7.65 percent each paid by employer and  employee) on incomes up to $61,200.
While all workers have suffered  from skyrocketing payroll taxes, the burden has
been most severe  for working families with children. Social Security taxes,
unlike  regular income taxes, are not adjusted for the number of dependents  in
the family, so a working parent trying to support a family of  four feels the
sting of this tax far more sharply than a single person  at the same wage level.
The effect of Social Security taxation is  particularly severe on lower-income
parents; a family with an  income of $25,000 per year, for instance, pays $3,825
in payroll taxes.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 --> 
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>The Government Assault on Family Income. Direct federal  taxes as a share of
median family income has increased  dramatically over the past four decades. In
1948, effective tax rates equaled  3 percent of income for the average family of
four. By 1970,  they had risen to 16 percent; by 1994, to 24.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The income loss due to increased taxation has seriously  strained American
family finances and profoundly affected American  family life. Chart 4 shows the
effects of increases in federal  income and Social Security taxes since 1948 on
the finances of the  average family. Total pre-tax income for the median family
of four in  1994 was $56,608. <B><TT><A HREF="ftnt2.htm">4</A></TT></B>
 After taxes, this family's income fell to $45,104.  If federal taxes as a
percentage of family income were restored  to 1948 levels, the family's post-tax
income would have  been $10,084 higher, or $55,188. In other words, the loss of
income  in 1992 because of the increase in federal taxes as a share of  family
income, due to the falling value of the personal exemption and  the rise in
Social Security taxes since the late 1940s, was $10,084.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This income loss severely affects the ability of families to  support
themselves. For example, the typical family of four has  monthly mortgage
payments of $664 and grocery bills of $332. Thus  the $10,084 in income lost to
this family due to the 45-year rise  in federal taxes costs this family 15
months worth of mortgage  payments, or 12 months mortgage combined with six
months worth  of groceries.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Solution: Tax Credits for Children</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are two practical ways to reduce the tax burden on  families with
children: by increasing the value of the personal exemption  or 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->  by allowing for the use of tax
credits. Although many positive  arguments can be made for increasing the
personal exemption,  the tax credit is better in the long run because it is less
complex  and can be used more effectively to reduce the tax burden on 
lower-income working families.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>With an income tax exemption, income equal to the amount of  the exemption
is excluded from tax. However, the actual tax savings  a family receives from
such an exemption will depend upon the  tax rate to which it is subject. Thus,
for a family in the 15 percent  income tax bracket, a $500 increase in the
dependent exemption  decreases income taxes by $75. A $1,000 increase in the 
exemption, as some have proposed, decreases a family's tax burden by  $150. But
for a family in the 28 percent tax bracket, a $1,000 increase  in the personal
exemption reduces the income tax burden by $280   86 percent more tax relief
than for families in the 15  percent bracket.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>By contrast, under a tax credit, the amount of the credit is  deducted from
taxes paid  below the line, so to speak  directly  reducing tax liability. Also,
unlike a tax exemption, a credit gives the  same amount of tax relief to every
taxpayer, regardless of income or  tax rate status. The two examples below, one
for a family of four  earning $30,000 per year and the other for the same family
 earning $75,000 per year, show clearly how the credit works.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Example #1:</B> Under current law, a family earning $30,000 per  year
(which puts it in the 15 percent income tax bracket) has an  income tax
liability of $1,988. Because this family has two children,  the $500 child tax
credit reduces the income tax bill by $1,000  leaving a net income tax bill of
$988. This is a 50 percent reduction in  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 -->  family's tax burden.
</P>
<P>
</P> 
<P><B>Example #2:</B> Under current law, a family earning $75,000 per  year
(which puts it in the 28 percent income tax bracket) has a tax  liability of
$8,114. Deducting $1,000  $500 for each child   leaves this family with a net
income tax bill of $7,114. This is a 11  percent reduction in the family's tax
burden.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Crushing Burden of Social Security</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Much of this chapter has focused on the crushing burden of  taxes in general
and the anti-growth features of the income tax in  particular. No treatment of
federal taxation would be complete,  however, without some discussion of the
interrelated problems of  the payroll tax and the Social Security retirement
system. The need  for reform is critical. The Bipartisan Entitlement Commission 
estimates that Social Security faces an unfunded liability of $7.3  trillion.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The burden of financing Social
Security has reached crisis  proportions. First, the payroll tax rate has risen
dramatically over  time. As the attached chart illustrates, the payroll tax has
jumped from  2 percent in 1949 to 15.3 percent today (the government  promotes
the fiction that half is paid by the employer and half by the  employee; in
reality, of course, the full burden is borne by the  worker in the form of lower
take-home pay). Of the 15.3 percent  payroll tax, 12.4 percent is dedicated to
Social Security, and 2.9 percent  is used to finance Medicare spending.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The rapidly rising tax rate is only part of the
problem. When  Social Security was created in the 1930s, only the first $3,000
of  in
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 -->  come was subject to tax. As the
graph demonstrates, however,  the amount of income subject to tax has
skyrocketed to more  than $60,000. The combination of these two effects  higher
tax  rates and an increase in the amount of wages that can be taxed   has caused
the payroll tax to become the biggest tax burden for  the majority of taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     In 1937, the maximum tax bill for the program
was $60.  Twenty years later, in 1957, the maximum tax bill was less than $170. 
By 1977, it had climbed to more than $1,600. Today, a worker's  Social Security
tax bill can reach more than $7,500. The 2.9  percent Medicare portion of the
payroll tax compounds the burden,  particularly because there is no limit on the
amount of income  subject to this additional levy. This spiraling tax bill has a
negative  economic impact. The payroll tax is an unambiguous hindrance to  job
creation, lowering take-home pay and reducing the level of  labor-force
participation.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The other major flaw in the Social Security system is that it  is bankrupt.
Simply stated, the Social Security system has  promised benefits that cannot be
delivered. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>According to the most recent report from the Social Security 
Administration, the system will begin running a deficit in about  15 years.
<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm">5</A></B></TT>  Politicians
claim that the Trust Fund will be able to  keep the system afloat for another 20
years until it, too, goes  bankrupt and the entire system collapses shortly
before 2030. One  small problem: The Trust Fund is a hoax; politicians have been
 spending the surplus every year and leaving behind nothing but  IOUs. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#6">6</A></B></TT>  As a result, the crisis
will begin when the system begins to face a  cash deficit around the year 2010 
about 15 years from now.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 --> 
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>The looming bankruptcy of Social Security is the result of a  system that
has allowed lawmakers to vote for future benefits well  in excess of the
system's capacity to pay for them. Unfortunately,  the day of reckoning is fast
approaching, and legislators now  must face these problems.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1993, with nary a vote to spare in either the House or the  Senate,
President Clinton managed to obtain approval for the  largest tax increase in
history. In his second year, 1994, he proposed   but ultimately failed to get
enacted  an even larger tax increase  to pay for his government-run health care
scheme. Then, on  December 16, 1994, shortly after the mid-term elections that
put a  Republican majority in the House for the first time in 40 years, the 
President reversed himself and proposed a &quot;Middle-Class Bill  of Rights&quot;
which included modest tax cuts for families with  children, tax deductions for
education expenses, and an expansion of  Individual Retirement Accounts. This
effort was short-lived,  however, because the Administration spent much of the
rest of 1995  opposing the tax cuts proposed by the Republican Congress.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>President Clinton's record tax increase was a complete failure.  Tax
revenues are rising slower than they did during the  tax-cutting Reagan years.
The Clinton tax hike also hindered deficit  reduction. The following chart shows
CBO projections of annual budget  deficits after the Clinton tax increase. After
a modest decline, due  primarily to the economy's slow climb out of the early
1990s  slow
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->  down, projected budget deficits
begin to climb rapidly,  reaching more than $400 billion after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Higher taxes also slow income growth for American families.  The following
charts illustrate the strong relationship between  taxes and family incomes.
During the Reagan years, income rose,  reversing the dismal economic performance
of the Carter years  when payroll tax hikes and bracket creep resulted in major
tax  increases. Unfortunately, Ronald Reagan's pro-growth policies were 
reversed by the Bush and Clinton Administrations. The effect on  the economy was
both predictable and inevitable: Incomes again  began to fall. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>During the 1980s, Reagan's opponents charged that the rich  were getting
richer and the poor were getting poorer. As the  numbers clearly show, however,
all income classes benefited from  the economy's performance. For the most part,
conversely, all  income classes suffer when the economy falters. The only
exception to  this trend has been during the Clinton Administration when, for 
the first time, the rich actually have become richer as the poor  have grown
poorer. The lesson from these statistics is clear:  Higher taxes slow the
economy, but the rich usually can adjust their  affairs to limit the damage,
leaving the poor most vulnerable to  the downturn.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Reagan Years</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Some Americans have been seduced into thinking that the tax  burden is too
low. They have been told, often by the  establishment media, that &quot;Reagan
era&quot; tax cuts starved the government of  revenue and that higher taxes are
needed simply to offset the effect  of 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 -->  these the massive cuts. 
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>As Chart 8 illustrates, however, there was no loss of tax  revenue during
the Reagan years. The effect is particularly  pronounced when one realizes that
the Reagan tax cuts were phased in, and  the economy did not actually receive a
net tax cut until January  1, 1983.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Even using 1981 as the base year (and effectively blaming  Reagan for the
recession that began during Carter's last fiscal year),  tax revenues expanded
from $599 billion in 1981 to $991 billion  in 1989. Even after adjusting for
inflation, revenues grew by 20  percent. Compare this to the level of revenue
growth under the  high-tax regimes of Bush and Clinton. As the <a href="tax_8.gif">chart</a> shows, tax 
revenues grew faster under the Reagan tax cuts than they have in  recent years
under higher tax rates.<TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#7">7</A></B></TT></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Critics claim that the Reagan tax cuts caused the deficit to  climb, but
this accusation does not withstand scrutiny. As the  following graph shows, the
deficit began to increase two fiscal years  before Ronald Reagan became
President and continued to rise during  his first two years in office, until the
economy received a  significant net tax cut on January 1, 1983. From that point
on, the deficit  began to shrink, falling to about $150 billion by the time
Reagan  left office.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Perhaps most important of all, the deficit would have continued  to fall had
Reagan's policies been left in place. In January 1989   the month Ronald Reagan
left office  the Democratically  controlled Congressional Budget Office
published estimates showing  what would happen to the deficit if Reagan's
policies were left in  place. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 -->  As <a href=tax_10.gif">Chart 10</a> shows, the CBO
projected that the deficit would  continue to fall every year. Unfortunately,
both George Bush and  Bill Clinton raised taxes, causing economic growth to
falter and  discouraging taxpayers from earning and reporting more taxable 
income, and the deficit increased.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The evidence is clear. Notwithstanding all the Washington  rhetoric, the tax
burden is too high. The deficit is the result of  excessive spending, not low
tax rates. The evidence of the past 20 years  confirms that high tax rates and
rising tax burdens mean higher  deficits.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Abandoned Families</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Clinton campaigned for President by promising to give tax cuts  to working
families with children, but he did little to honor  this promise until after the
electorate brought new leadership to  Congress in 1994. Almost one year after
introducing his  &quot;Middle-Class Bill of Rights,&quot; Clinton again
abandoned families when he  vetoed the Balanced Budget Act of 1995, which had as
its centerpiece  a $500-per-child tax credit for working families. Clinton 
claimed, among other things, that proposed reforms in the earned  income tax
credit (EITC) included in the plan would raise taxes on  families earning less
than $30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Yet a comparison of President Clinton's &quot;Middle-Class Bill  of Rights&quot;
(with its $300-per-child tax credit for dependent  children below age 13 in
families with annual incomes below  $75,0008) and the Balanced Budget Act vetoed
by Clinton (with its  $500-per-child tax cut forall children in families earning
up to  $110,0009) shows that the congressional plan would benefit 5.4 million 
more 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->  low-income working families with
children than the Clinton  plan, even after accounting for changes in the EITC
in the  Balanced Budget Act. Many families with children and annual incomes 
below $24,000 would be denied the $300 child credit under  the Clinton plan
(receiving only the EITC) but would be eligible  for both the $500 child credit
and the EITC under the  congressional plan.
</P>
<P>
</P> 
<P>Overall, Congress's $500-per-child tax credit would benefit  23 million more
children than the Administration's  $300-per-child credit. Congress would give
tax relief to 10.4 million families  with children who would receive no tax
relief under the Clinton plan.  In addition, there would be millions of families
under the  Clinton plan in which at least one sibling received tax relief but
others  did not. Taken together, the number of children not qualifying for  any
tax relief under Clinton would be 23 million less than under  the Balanced
Budget Act. These children would receive $15.4  billion in tax relief under the
BBA but nothing under the Clinton plan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are three major reasons why the Clinton plan denies tax  relief to so
many families with children:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reason #1:</B> Clinton's tax cut benefits only families with  children
under age 13, denying tax relief to the families of at least 2.8  million other
children whose parents earn less than $30,000 per year. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reason #2:</B> Clinton's tax cut phases out for families earning 
between $60,000 and $75,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reason #3:</B> The Clinton plan requires low-income families to  deduct
their EITC benefits from their income tax bill before  taking 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  the $300-per-child tax credit. By
contrast, the Balanced  Budget Act allows a low-income family to take the
$500-per-child  tax credit first, then receiving the full measure of the EITC on
top  of the child credit. <B><TT><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#10">10</A></TT></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>These three elements of the Clinton plan make it substantially  inferior to
Congress's $500-per-child tax credit, even considering  the reforms in the EITC.
Specifically:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Clinton's $300-per-child tax credit
would benefit 23 million  fewer children than Congress's $500-per-child tax
credit. Some 10.4  million families would get no tax relief under the Clinton
plan  but would under the BBA. Millions of other families would  receive reduced
tax relief because some of their children would  qualify under Congress's plan
but not under Clinton's. Taken  together, these families would be denied $15
billion per year in tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The Clinton plan would deny tax relief to 5.4
million children  in families earning below $30,000 per year. Under Congress's 
plan, these same families would receive $2.3 billion in tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Under the Clinton plan, a single parent with one
child would  have to earn over $18,500 per year to become eligible for the 
$300-per-child tax credit. Under the Balanced Budget Act, this parent  would
begin getting tax relief with just over $11,500 in annual income.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Under the Clinton plan, a married couple with
two children  would have to make $24,000 per year to become eligible for the 
$300-per-child tax cut. Under the congressional plan, this family  would begin
getting tax relief at $17,000 in annual income.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P> 
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Under the Balanced Budget Act, the average tax
relief per  family is $856; under the Clinton plan, it is only $442.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>THE 104TH CONGRESS
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The centerpiece of the new Congress's Contract With  America was a
commitment to pass a plan that balances the budget by  2002, provides
substantial tax relief to families with children and  seniors, creates jobs, and
spurs economic growth. The new House  leadership rightly understood that tax
cuts must be included in any  credible balanced budget plan for both economic
and political  reasons. First, cutting taxes gives the economy a needed boost
while  Washington curbs spending in order to balance the budget.  Economic
models show that cutting taxes while balancing the budget  produces higher
economic growth than balancing the budget  without tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There also is a political element to cutting taxes while  balancing the
budget. Tax cuts  especially broad-based cuts such as  the $500-per-child tax
credit and capital gains reform  build  powerful constituencies to counter the
entrenched interests who  survive by exploiting government programs. In the
absence of tax  cuts, these pro-spending lobbies would be the only voices heard 
during any debate over balancing the budget. So, too, tax cuts  &quot;sugar-coat&quot;
the political pain of spending cuts. For example, families  in the typical
congressional district would receive some $54  million per year from the
$500-per-child tax credit. It is difficult to  imagine that any single federal
spending project of similar  magnitude could benefit as many constituents at the
same time. Thus, the  political advantages of tax cuts more than outweigh the
political  disadvantages of cutting spending.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The good news for hard-pressed families and businesses is that  tax cuts
were at the forefront of the agenda during the 1995-1996  budget debate and that
the new Congress fulfilled its promise to  deliver a balanced budget plan with
tax cuts to Bill Clinton. The  bad news is that Clinton vetoed the balanced
budget and tax cut plan   just two years after signing the largest tax increase
in history   and that the vision of taking taxpayers' money back from 
Washington became a victim of the &quot;green eyeshade&quot; negotiations over
how  to balance the budget.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Tax Cuts in the House Plan</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>On May 18, 1995, the House of Representatives passed, by a  vote of 238 to
193, its sweeping budget blueprint  formally known  as the budget resolution  to
balance the budget in seven years  while providing over $350 billion in tax cuts
to help families with  children and seniors and spur economic growth. Although 
many Washington insiders charged that the projected tax cut was  too large (some
$354 billion over seven years), it amounted to  returning to taxpayers only 3
percent of the $11.5 trillion in total  tax revenues the government expects to
collect over the same  seven-year period.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Key elements of the House plan included:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Family Tax Relief:</B> A $500-per-child tax credit for every  working
family earning up to $200,000 per year, a $150 tax credit to  reduce the
marriage penalty, a $5,000 tax credit for adoption  expenses, and a $500 tax
credit for the care of elderly relatives.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 --> 
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Pro-Growth Tax Cuts:</B> A 50 percent cut in the effective  capital
gains tax for individuals, expanded Individual Retirement  Accounts, improved
depreciation schedules for capital expenses,  a reformed alternative minimum
tax, and higher thresholds on  estate and gift taxes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Tax Cuts for Seniors:</B> Repeal of the Social Security Surtax  passed
in 1994, modification of the Social Security earnings test, and  improved tax
treatment of long-term care and life insurance. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Tax Cuts in the Senate Plan</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfortunately, the Senate-passed budget resolution failed to  provide
explicit tax cuts. The Senate plan did allow for  unspecified tax cuts for
families and economic growth, but only if CBO  certified that the plan would
balance the budget in seven years.  Once this certification had been made, tax
cuts could be financed  with the $170 billion economic windfall, or &quot;fiscal
dividend,&quot; the  CBO estimated would accrue to the government from lower 
interest rates and the increased tax revenues generated by higher  economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Tax Cuts in the Balanced Budget Act of 1995</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>After considerable negotiation, the House and Senate agreed  that the
Balanced Budget Act of 1995 (BBA) should contain $245  billion in tax cuts to
help families and spur economic growth. The  net size of this tax cut package is
reduced to $218 billion after  deducting $27 billion in revenues generated from
closing special  tax breaks for certain corporations and industries. Though this
 plan has come under considerable criticism from the media and  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 24 -->  Washington elite, it actually is
rather modest: Overall, it  promises to return to taxpayers roughly 2 percent of
the $11.5 trillion in  tax revenues the government expects to collect over the
next  seven years. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A full 65 percent of the tax cut plan is targeted to families,  especially
families with children. The &quot;crown jewel&quot; is a  $500-per-child tax
credit benefiting 28 million families raising 51  million children. The
remaining 35 percent of the plan is dedicated to  tax cuts to spur new
investment, jobs, and economic growth. A  small portion of the plan includes two
important tax provisions to  help seniors with their health care costs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Highlights of the BBA plan include:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>1. $500-per-Child Tax Credit.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The centerpiece of the Republican Contract With America and  of
the House-passed plan is a $500-per-child tax credit benefiting  28 million
working families raising some 51 million children.  The $500-per-child credit is
&quot;non-refundable,&quot; meaning the total  value of the credit may not
exceed a family's income tax bill. But it  does provide uniform tax relief to
all families with incomes up  to $110,000 per year, thereby reducing a
low-income family's  tax burden by a much greater proportion than an 
upper-income family's. For taxpayers filing jointly with incomes  above
$110,000, the credit phases out at a rate of $25 for each $1,000  in earnings
above the threshold (a range of $20,000), phasing  out fully at $130,000 in
income. For families with two children,  the two credits for which they are
eligible are phased out fully  at 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->  $150,000 in income. For single
filers, the credit begins to  phase out at $75,000 in income.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P> 
<P>There are sound policy reasons to cut taxes for families with  children:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Families with children are overtaxed.</B> In 1948, the
average  American family with children paid only 3 percent of its income to 
Uncle Sam. Today, the same family pays 24.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Giving a family of four a $500-per-child tax credit is equivalent  to
giving that family one month's mortgage payment and  one month's groceries.</B>
The average family spends $644 per month  in mortgage payments and $332 per
month on groceries. Thus,  the $1,000 in tax relief the congressional plan would
give to a  family with two children would help this family pay one month's 
mortgage and groceries.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Millions of families stand to benefit.</B> The families of 51  million
American children (28 million taxpaying families) are eligible  for the
$500-per-child tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Family tax relief helps families in every state.</B> The typical 
congressional district has some 117,000 children in families eligible for  a
$500 tax credit. Thus, families in the typical district would  receive $54
million per year in tax relief. Tables showing the benefits  of family tax
relief by state and congressional district are included  in the appendix to this
chapter.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Congress's $500-per-child tax credit would eliminate the  entire income
tax burden for 3.5 million taxpayers caring for 8.7  million 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 -->  children.</B> These 3.5 million
families would receive over $2.2  billion per year in tax relief. Families with
two children earning up  to $24,000 per year would see their entire income tax
burden  eliminated by a $500-per-child tax credit, and families with three 
children and incomes as high as $26,000 also would have their  income tax bill
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Most families are middle-class</B>. The $500 child credit directs  89
percent of all benefits to families with adjusted gross incomes  below $75,000
per year  middle-income by any standard   and over 96 percent to families with
incomes below $100,000.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Cutting taxes for all families  regardless of income  is  fair.</B>
Congress's plan would cut the income tax burden of a family  of four earning
$30,000 per year by 51 percent and the income  tax burden of a family earning
$40,000 per year by 30 percent.  Meanwhile, a family of four earning $75,000
would see their tax  burden reduced by 12 percent, and a family earning $100,000
per  year would receive a tax cut of just 7.4 percent.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2. Higher Standard Deduction to Reduce the Marriage Penalty.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Under current law, dual-income married couples who file a  joint return can
end up paying more taxes than two single  taxpayers filing individually. The BBA
takes a small step toward  reducing this &quot;marriage penalty&quot; by
increasing the value of the  standard deduction for these working couples
relative to the value of  the same deduction for singles. In 1996, for instance,
the ratio of  the standard deduction for married couples would be 1.68 of the 
value of the individual deduction. By 2005 and beyond, the ratio  would 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 -->  be 2.00.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P><B>3. Tax Credit for Adoption.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The estimated two million families ready to adopt children  face huge
expenses during the adoption process, but current tax  law does not allow them
to deduct adoption costs from their tax  bill. The BBA plan makes a substantial
commitment to  encouraging adoption by giving adoptive families a tax credit of
$5,000 to  offset such expenses as adoption fees, court costs, attorneys' fees, 
and other related expenses. This credit is available in full to  families
earning up to $75,000 per year and phased out gradually for  families earning up
to $115,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>4. Tax Deduction for Dependent Parents.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The current tax code provides little relief for the care of  elderly parents
or grandparents. The standard personal exemption  of $2,500 is available, but,
as with the dependent child  exemption, the value of the credit is greater for
middle - and  upper-income families than for modest-income families in the 15
percent  income bracket. For example, while the standard deduction of $2,500 
allows a family in the 15 percent bracket to lower its income tax  by $375, the
same deduction allows a family in the 28 percent  bracket to lower its tax by
$700.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The BBA plan offers additional tax relief for the care of  parents and
grandparents in the form of an &quot;above-the-line&quot; deduction  of $1,000
per family member. Such a credit could help many  families 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 28 -->  that prefer to care for elderly
relatives at home but cannot  afford the expense.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>5. Favorable Tax Treatment for Private Long-Term Care.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Although medical expenses are deductible from federal taxes  when they
exceed a certain percentage of income, long-term care  expenses today generally
are not tax-deductible. Under the  BBA, starting in 1996, long-term care
insurance generally would  be treated the same as accident and health insurance,
and  employers would be allowed to provide their employees with tax-free 
long-term care insurance just as they now often provide medical  benefits.
Eligible long-term care premiums and expenses for  qualified long-term care
services would be treated the same as other  medical expenses, and benefits
received under a long-term care  insurance policy would be tax-free (up to $175
per day).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Placing long-term care benefits on the same basis as health  care and
financing them under tax provisions similar to those for  medical insurance
could lead to substantial savings for state and  federal programs supporting
nursing home care.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>6. Accelerated Payment of Life Insurance Benefits for the  Terminally
Ill.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Under current law, life insurance benefits are not taxed, but  insured
individuals and their families have no way to obtain  benefits prior to death
without a severe income tax liability  even  though many insurance companies are
willing to offer such  &quot;accelerated 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 29 -->  benefits.&quot;  The BBA tax cut
plan would facilitate the practice  by which some insurance providers pay
benefits prior to death if  the insured person is terminally or chronically ill.
The plan would  allow such payments to be excluded from a taxpayer's gross 
income, just as payments to a surviving beneficiary now are. In addition,  it
would allow similar tax-exempt treatment for amounts  received from the sale or
assignment of a life insurance contract to a  qualified settlement provider.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>7. Reduction in Capital Gains Tax.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The U.S. tax code punishes capital investment by taxing  investment income
more than once: twice by taxing corporate and  individual income, and then a
third time by taxing capital gains.  The current maximum tax rate on capital
gains is 28 percent for  individuals and 35 percent for corporations, and these
gains are  not indexed to the inflation rate. By contrast, most of America's 
major economic competitors, such as Japan or Germany, either  exempt capital
gains from taxation or tax them at a greatly reduced  rate, often indexing the
basis of the gains to inflation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The BBA lessens this penalty in two ways. First, it lowers the  effective
maximum capital gains rate to 19.8 percent for  individuals and 28 percent for
corporations. Second, starting January 1,  2001, it permits individuals to index
the value of assets to ensure  that they are not being taxed on purely
inflationary gains. The bill  also includes a 14 percent maximum rate for the
sale of small  business stock by a taxpayer other than a corporation. A
qualifying  small business may not have gross assets of more than $50 million at
 the time the stock is issued. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 30 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As will be seen below, these measures would have a  substantial impact on
the long-term growth of the economy while the  budget is being balanced.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>8. New Individual Retirement Accounts.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In addition to Individual Retirement Accounts (IRAs), the bill  offers
another way for taxpayers to preserve the value of this  retirement savings by
creating a new American Dream IRA (AD  IRA). Contributions would be made from
post-tax income, but the  interest from such savings would not be taxed upon
withdrawal if  contributions have remained in the account for at least five
years  and the retiree has reached age 59 1/2. This is why the  American Dream
Savings account is sometimes known as a  &quot;back-ended&quot; IRA. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Initially, contributions to the new ADS account would be  limited to $2,000
per taxpayer per year ($4,000 for a married couple),  but this amount would be
indexed to the rate of inflation in  subsequent years. The plan also allows
penalty-free withdrawals for a  first-time home purchase or to pay certain
educational or medical  expenses.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>9. Alternative Minimum Tax. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Current tax law imposes an alternative minimum tax (AMT)  on certain
individuals and corporations whose tax liability, after  deductions and credits,
falls below the level specified by the  alternative minimum tax rate. For
individuals, the minimum tax is  im
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 31 -->  posed at graduated rates of 26
and 28 percent; for corporations,  it is imposed at 20 percent. In computing
their AMT, individuals  and corporations must adjust the annual amount they
deduct for  depreciated assets so that their tax liability does not fall below
the  AMT amount. 
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>The bill modifies the AMT for both individual and corporate  taxpayers by
repealing the depreciation adjustment for  property placed in service after
1995, thereby conforming AMT  depreciation methods with the method used for
regular tax  purposes. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#11">11</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>10. Estate and Gift Tax Reform
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The BBA makes several important changes in the estate and  gift tax code to
reduce the punishing effects of this tax on estates,  especially the estates of
small businesses and farms. The bill  gradually increases the current effective
exemption of $600,000  to $750,000 in $25,000 increments through 2001, after
which  the effective exemption amount is indexed to inflation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For the estates of small businesses, which do not have special  tax rules,
the bil effectively excludes an amount equal to $1.75  million of the business's
value from the decedent's  estate. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#12">12</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Economic Benefits of the Tax Cuts</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Washington insiders, especially those within the White House  and some in
Congress, argued throughout 1995 that cutting taxes  was inconsistent with the
goal of balancing the budget. They  claimed, for instance, that Washington &quot;could
not afford&quot; to reduce  taxes 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 32 -->  while so much spending was being
cut to balance the  budget. These criticisms ignore the economic benefits that
would be  realized from combining tax cuts with a balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To demonstrate this point, economists at The Heritage  Foundation used one
of the principal econometric models of the U.S.  economy to project the economic
effects of the tax cut elements of the  Balanced Budget Act. This analysis
showed that:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The Balanced Budget Act with tax
cuts would add $146  billion more to gross domestic product (GDP) over seven
years than  the same plan without tax cuts. This comes to some $1,500 per 
household.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The reduction in taxes on capital (including
capital gains tax  relief) accounts for $86.3 billion of this additional GDP and
leads  to a stronger economy in the long run. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#13">13
</A></B></TT></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     The Balanced Budget Act with tax cuts would add
$191  billion more to GDP over seven years than the same plan without tax  cuts.
This comes to about $2,000 per household.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Many individual industries would benefit. For
example, a  balanced budget with tax cuts would result in the production of an 
additional 400,000 new cars and 20,000 new homes.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>While balancing the budget is good for long-term  economic growth, even more
growth is generated by the tax cuts in the  Balanced Budget Act. The tax cuts on
family income  primarily  the $500-per-child tax credit  would allow more
households to  save or spend their hard-earned money instead of sending it to 
Wash
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 33 -->  ington, and this increased
private savings and spending would  help offset reductions in government
spending. In the long run,  increased private-sector activity with less
government  spending means a more efficient economy, more well-paying jobs, and 
a lower rate of inflation.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>During the early years of any reduction in government  spending, the economy
must adjust to a lower level of government  intervention. Businesses that
previously produced goods and services  for the government now must produce for
the private sector,  and workers previously employed by the government must find
 new jobs in the private sector. Analogously, there must be a  transition in
savings and investment. Money that would have been  invested in United States
bonds must be re-directed toward  private-sector securities, bonds, or other
vehicles. The transition from  government spending to private savings and
spending is necessary  and valuable, but it also takes time. In the short term,
returning  money to the private sector by means of the $500-per-child tax credit
 will help to offset these negative effects.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The tax cuts on capital income  especially the capital gains  tax reductions
 are necessary to ensure a stronger economy.  There are two reasons for this:
First, reducing the tax on capital  gains lowers the cost of moving an
investment from an average  company to one that is exceptionally productive and
well-run. This  lowering of the &quot;switching&quot; costs means that investors
will play a larger  role in promoting well-run, productive companies. Thus, the 
economy as a whole is likely to be more efficient. Second, lower taxes  on
capital cause the cost of capital to fall. Lenders, for example,  do not need to
charge quite as much interest on capital loans to  recoup the taxes they paid
when making the capital available to a  bor
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 34 -->  rower. Lower capital costs
usually mean more investment by  businesses in labor-saving equipment, which
commonly results in  increased labor productivity. This increased productivity 
translates into higher wages and, through the division of labor, more jobs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Individual Benefits of the Tax Cuts</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As the 1995-1996 budget debate wore on, the &quot;green  eyeshade&quot;
negotiations over how to balance the budget overshadowed  the benefits of tax
cuts to families and individual taxpayers.  President Clinton often charged that
the $245 billion tax cut package  was &quot;extreme,&quot; given how much
spending had to be reduced in order  to balance the budget. But the plan
actually is relatively modest:  It amounts to returning just 2 cents of every
dollar of the $11.5  trillion the federal government expects to collect in tax
revenues  over the next seven years. At the same time, the Washington elite 
often dismissed the $500-per-child tax cut as insignificant. For  most
hard-working American families, however, $500 is not only a  significant amount
of money, but could mean the difference  between paying and not paying the
mortgage.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For instance, the $500-per-child tax credit would eliminate  100 percent of
the income tax liability for families of four earning  up to $24,000 a year and
more than 50 percent of the income tax  liability for a family of four earning
$30,000 a year.  Moreover, while $500 may buy only a hammer in Washington, it
would  buy much more for the average family with two children. For  example, the
$500-per-child tax credit would cover any of the  following expenses for an
average family with two children:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     3 months of groceries,
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 35 --> 
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     1.5 months of mortgage payments,
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     15 months of health insurance,
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     15 months of telephone bills, or
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     11 months of electric bills.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Critics of the tax cut package claim that spending on education  and medical
security for the elderly would have to be compromised  to &quot;pay&quot; for
the tax cut. This short-sighted view ignores the  benefits that flow from
allowing families and retirees to keep and  spend their own money. It is the
view of those who cannot imagine  solving a problem without a government program
or handout.  However, consider the following:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>     If a family invested the entire
$500-per-child tax credit in an  education savings account, in 18 years there
would be enough  money to pay for a child's education at an average public
university.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>     Since senior citizens claim about 30 percent of
all capital  gains, cutting the capital gains tax in half would give them more 
disposable income to use for additional medical services and other  basic living
expenses.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>False Class Warfare Claims</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Liberals in Congress and the White House also claim that these  tax cuts
would benefit the rich at the expense of the poor. What are  the facts?
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 36 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>     At least 65 percent of the entire
$245 billion package of tax cuts  is targeted to families  especially families
with children.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>     89 percent of the benefits from the
$500-per-child tax cut  would go to families earning less than $75,000 per year 
and more  than 96 percent of the benefits would go to families earning less 
than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>     52 percent of the benefits from the capital
gains tax rate  reduction would go to households with incomes of less than
$100,000  from sources other than capital gains.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>     The average household declaring a capital gain
had income  of $58,729 from sources other than capital gains in 1991.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>     A total of 3.5 million working families caring
for 8.7 million  children would have their entire income tax liability erased by
 the $500-per-child tax credit.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>     Married couples with two children and and
incomes as high  as $24,000 per year would see their income tax burden erased.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>What is most ironic about the Administration's criticisms is  that the
congressional plan would benefit more working families  than the
Administration's own proposal, even after accounting for  the changes in the
earned income credit (EIC) called for in the  Balanced Budget Act. In
particular, many families with children  and incomes below $24,000 per year
would be denied the  $300-per-child credit under the Clinton plan (receiving
only the EIC)  but would be eligible for both the $500-per-child tax credit and 
the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 37 -->  EIC under the congressional plan.
Moreover:
</P> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>     5.4 million families earning below
$30,000 would be eligible for  a tax cut under the congressional plan but would
be denied  relief under President Clinton's plan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>*</CITE></B>      Under the congressional plan, a family of four
would be  eligible for a tax cut starting at an annual income level of $17,000. 
Under the Clinton plan, the same family would not be eligible without  an annual
income of at least $24,000.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>If Congress and the White House fail to reach an agreement  in 1996 on a
plan to balance the budget while providing tax cuts,  the first task of the
105th Congress should be to send a new tax  cut plan to the President that lays
the groundwork for a complete  overhaul of the federal tax code and the
enactment of a flat tax.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Americans are suffering from an income tax system that  punishes hard work,
penalizes thrift, and retards investment. To make  matters worse, the payroll
tax used to support the Social Security  system is at a record high. The
combination of these two tax  systems makes Americans worse off today and makes
it equally certain  that they will be worse off tomorrow. Both systems need to
be fixed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Elements of a Flat Tax</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Each of the income tax code's many shortcomings can be  addressed by
targeted legislation, but a far better approach is  simply to replace the
existing system with a flat tax. Whether the goal  is to address the major flaws
outlined earlier in this chapter or to  fix 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 38 -->  one of the current system's many
specific problems, the flat  tax does the job. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There have been many flat tax proposals over the years, but  they all share
certain key features. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>One low tax rate -</B> All flat tax proposals have a single
tax rate  that applies to all income subject to tax. The actual rate imposed 
varies, but the upper limit would be about 20 percent. The  Armey/Shelby flat
tax legislation, for instance, begins with a 20 percent  rate which phases down
to 17 percent after a couple of years.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Elimination of deductions, credits, and exemptions -</B>
All pure  flat tax proposals eliminate provisions of the tax code that bestow 
preferential tax treatment on certain behaviors and activities.  Included in
this would be special tax breaks for businesses and  corporations and, for
individual taxpayers, the home mortgage interest  deduction, the charitable
contributions deduction, and the state and  local income and property tax
deductions. The combination of no  preferences, one low rate, and a generous
family allowance would  allow taxpayers to file their tax returns on a
postcard-size form.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>One-time taxation of income  -</B> Flat tax proposals are designed  to
eliminate the tax code's bias against capital formation by  ending the double
(and sometimes triple and quadruple) taxation of  income generated through
savings and investment. This is  achieved by ensuring that all income,
regardless of how it is earned or  how it is spent, is treated equally. Several
important tax policy  decisions flow from this principle, including repeal of
the estate  and gift tax, elimination of the double taxation of capital gains 
and dividend income, and neutral treatment of savings, either  through 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 39 -->  an unlimited IRA or through
elimination of taxes on interest  income. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#14">14</A></B></TT>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P> 
<P><B>Benefits of a Flat Tax</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>By addressing so many problems in the existing tax code, the  flat tax would
have an immediate and dramatic impact.  Included among the many benefits are:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Faster economic growth -</B> A flat tax would spur
increased  work, saving, and investment. According to many economists, the rise 
in productive behavior would likely add one percentage point to  the annual rate
of economic growth. How significant is this?  An  increase in the growth rate of
just one-half of one percentage  point would boost an average family of four's
yearly income by  more than $5,000 after ten years.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Instant wealth creation -</B> The value of financial assets is 
determined by the after-tax income they generate over time. By  eliminating the
second, third, and fourth layers of taxation on  capital income, a flat tax
therefore would significantly boost the value  of all income-producing assets.
According to Professor  Dale Jorgenson of the Harvard Economics Department,
enactment of  a flat tax would boost wealth immediately by some $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Simplicity -</B> 600-plus tax forms would be swept into the trash  and
replaced by two simple postcard-size forms. Wage, salary,  and pension income
would be reported on the individual form,  and business and capital income would
be reported on the  business form. Neither form would require more than a few
minutes  to compile, substantially reducing the 5.4 billion hour yearly  burden
of today's tax code.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 40 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Fairness -</B> All taxpayers and all income would be treated  equally. A
taxpayer with ten times the taxable income of his  neighbor would pay ten times
as much in taxes. Successful entrepreneurs  no longer would be penalized by
discriminatory tax rates, and  no longer would the politically well-connected by
able to benefit  from special loopholes and preferences.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>An end to micromanagement and political favoritism -</B> All 
deductions, credits, exemptions, loopholes, and preferences would  be
eliminated. Politicians would lose their ability to pick winners  and losers,
reward friends and punish enemies, and use the tax code  to impose their values
on the economy. Investment decisions  would be guided by economic forces rather
than tax considerations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Increased civil liberties -</B> The complexity of the tax code makes  it
nearly impossible for taxpayers or IRS agents to follow the law.  A greatly
simplified tax code would eliminate virtually all of  the conflicts and
controversies that make the IRS one of the  most feared agencies of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Help for families -</B> The flat tax does have one exemption: All 
taxpayers, based on family size, are allowed to protect a base  amount of income
from taxation. In the Armey/Shelby legislation, a  family of four would not pay
taxes on income of less than $33,300. As  the attached <a href="tax_13.gif">chart</a> illustrates, this
large &quot;tax-free&quot; amount results  in either zero or very low tax rates
for lower - and  middle-income taxpayers.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Rescuing Retirement Security 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 41 --> 
</B>
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>The bailout of America's retirement system does not  necessarily have to
happen right away, but every year it is delayed  simply makes the ultimate
solution that much harder to achieve.  Fortunately, there is a way to avert this
crisis without reducing  benefits for those currently collecting benefits or
near retirement: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Reform Social Security.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Allow current workers to dedicate at least 2 percent, but 
preferably 4 percent, of their 12.4 percent Social Security payroll tax to  a
private Individual Retirement Account.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Thanks to compound interest, and free from the double tax  that normally is
applied to savings, these IRAs would generate  huge nest eggs for most workers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In exchange for being granted these IRAs, workers who  choose this option
would agree to forego some or all of their  promised Social Security payments
(determined by how close they are  to retirement age, with the guarantee that
retirement income  would be at least as high as currently promised by Social
Security).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Those now retired or near retirement would continue to get all  the benefits
promised, even though many of these individuals are  receiving far more than
they put into the system.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The difference between promised benefits and payroll tax  revenues under the
new system would be made up by transfers from  general revenues just as would be
required to finance the $2.5 trillion  unfunded liability under the current
system.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 42 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>In addition to rescuing Americans' retirement income, this  package also
would solve one of the major economic problems of  the current system  its
negative effect on savings. Because  taxpayers are under the illusion that the
government will take care of  their retirement, they have reduced their savings
significantly.  This means fewer resources with which to finance future 
economic growth. Lower levels of saving mean less money for consumers  to borrow
to buy cars and fewer funds available to families looking  to buy their first
home. Perhaps most important, a low level of  savings means that businesses and
entrepreneurs will not have  as much access to the capital they need to invest
in the future  productivity  and wages  of American workers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. How much faster will the economy grow with a flat tax?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Estimates vary, but reliable projections indicate the  economy's
growth rate will be somewhere between one-half of one  percent and one percent
higher for several years following the  enactment of a flat tax. What does this
mean?  If the economy grows just  one-half of one percent faster each year, the
average family of four  will enjoy more than $5,000 of additional income by the
tenth year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Will the elimination of the home mortgage interest  deduction hurt
the housing industry?
</B></P>
<P>
</P> 
<P><B>A.</B> Washington lobbyists representing real estate agents paid a 
consulting group to do a study of the flat tax. Not surprisingly,  the
consulting group concluded that a flat tax would lower  housing values by 15
percent. Independent research, however, has  found 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 43 -->  this result to be completely
unfounded. Indeed, if the itemized  deduction is so critical, why did the
housing market do so well in  the 1980s when lower tax rates increased the
after-tax cost of  home mortgage interest payments by as much as 135 percent? 
As  the above <a href="tax_14.gif">chart</a> illustrates, there appears to be no correlation  whatsoever
between the value of the itemized reduction and either  home sales or home
values. Instead, the key to strong real estate  markets is a growing economy.
This is why realtors, homebuilders,  and homeowners will benefit from a flat
tax.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Would charities be harmed if the charitable contributions  deduction
was eliminated?</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> As is the case with housing, the evidence from the  1980s clearly
shows that charities have nothing to fear from a flat  tax. The graphs
demonstrate that charitable contributions more  than doubled during the 1980s
even though the tax benefit of giving  fell sharply. Likewise, the numbers show
that charitable giving  rises with income; thus, since a flat tax will boost
income, charities  will benefit.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Are there any groups that would pay more under a flat tax?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The flat tax is not a free lunch. Aggressive users of tax 
shelters could face higher tax bills. Wealthy wage earners who create  business
losses to cancel out their tax liabilities will lose that  gimmick under a flat
tax. Many businesses could see their tax bills go up  as well. Needless to say,
the political prospects for a flat tax  increase to the extent that the number
of &quot;losers&quot; is minimized. This is  a strong argument for maximizing
the size of the tax cut that  accompanies tax reform.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 44 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Why do some opponents say dividends and interest would  not be taxed
with a flat tax?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Probably because they do not understand how the  proposal works.
Under the flat tax, capital income is taxed at the  business level. What changes
is that corporate profits are no longer  subject to a second layer of tax at the
individual level. In a flat tax  system, a dividend check becomes analogous to a
worker's paycheck   an amount of money left after taxes already have been paid. 
Similarly, interest income is taxed by making it non-deductible to  the
borrower. A company with $1 million in interest payments,  for instance, would
pay $170,000 in taxes on that amount. To tax  this income a second time by
including it in the taxable income of  the recipient would be double taxation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What happens to the capital gains tax?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Like all other provisions which double or triple tax income,  the
capital gains tax disappears. Individual taxpayers who buy  assets have paid
taxes on that income already. Whether that asset goes  up or down in value after
the purchase does not matter, since the  tax already has been paid. Businesses,
because they are able to  deduct the cost of purchasing assets, would pay tax on
asset sales.  This taxes the capital gain (if any exists), but avoids double
taxation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Will the estate tax disappear with a flat tax?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Estate and gift taxes are one of the clearest examples of  double
and triple taxation in the current tax code and will be  eliminated under the
flat tax. In addition to protecting the taxpayer from  hav
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 45 -->  ing to pay additional taxes on
income that already has been  taxed, abolishing the estate tax prevents family
businesses and  farms from being sold off for tax purposes. Another argument for
 elimination is that the estate tax drains private capital from the  economy
that is needed to finance future economic growth.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What happens to the IRS?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> No tax reform proposal will eliminate the IRS. As long as  the
government intends to claim $1.4 trillion of tax revenue,  some level of tax
collection authority will be required. By radically  simplifying the tax code
and eliminating the provisions that cause  the most conflict (alternative
minimum tax, depreciation,  capital gains, itemized deductions, etc.), the flat
tax will significantly  reduce IRS abuses. For individual taxpayers, the only
things the  IRS will be able to question are total income and number of
children.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Will a flat tax encourage job creation?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> A flat tax will encourage more jobs and higher wages by  boosting
incentives to work, save, and invest. In the long run, the  elimination of most
of the tax code's bias against savings and  investment will have the biggest
effect. As studies show, a flat tax  will encourage capital formation, leading
over time to higher levels  of productivity, increased wages, and more jobs. A
flat tax also  will have a more immediate impact on job creation, however, by 
making work more attractive. High tax rates drive a wedge  between what it costs
a business to employ a worker and how much  the worker receives in take-home
pay. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#15">15</A></B></TT>  By
increasing the cost  of labor, taxes lower the number of workers a company is
willing  to hire. Businesses do not exist to pay workers more than they  are 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 46 -->  worth. They exist to make money
and will hire only as long as  the value of each new worker's additional output
exceeds the total  cost of employing that worker.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>When politicians enact policies that raise the cost of  employment, the
total cost of some workers will rise above the value they  bring their
employers. In the long run, a business has only two  options when faced with
this predicament: close its doors or lay off  workers who are net money losers.
Even workers who retain their  jobs pay a price. Taxes on labor income, whether
paid by employee  or employer, dollar for dollar, unavoidably reduce the amount 
that finds its way into their paychecks. Politicians may pretend  otherwise, but
every time the tax burden climbs, workers' after-tax  income declines. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#16">16</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Would a flat tax reduce the budget deficit?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> This depends on which flat tax is implemented. More 
specifically, it depends on the tax rate and whether the proposal  includes
limits on government spending. Even though lower rates  generally stimulate
economic growth and expand the tax base, at some  point they translate into less
revenue. A flat tax of 20 percent, for  instance, almost certainly would raise
more money than a flat tax  of 10 percent. The size of the personal
exemption/family  allowance also plays a key role, since the decision to protect
a certain  amount of income ($36,800 for a family of four in last year's Armey 
bill) generally means the rate on taxable income must be higher.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>According to a Treasury Department analysis leaked to the  media before the
1994 elections, the Administration estimates that  the Armey flat tax would
result in a $244 billion revenue loss to  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 47 -->  federal government in 1995. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#17">17</A></B></TT>  But this study contained
a  $500 billion error, as the Department later  admitted, <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#18">18</A></B></TT> and used the 17 percent
rate to analyze 1995 revenues even though the Armey  bill calls explicitly for
an initial rate of 20 percent (which would  be phased down to 17 percent). The
Treasury Department now  claims that, once fully phased in, the Armey flat tax
would &quot;cost&quot;  the government as much as $186 billion per year. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#19">19</A></B></TT> Because it  is based on
static analysis, however, this figure assumes that  reduced tax rates and
simplification would have no positive effect on  the economy. Hence, it ignores
the additional revenues produced  by income growth (as well as the binding caps
on federal  spending that the Armey bill would impose). <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#20">20</A>
</B></TT></P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>A flat tax almost certainly would reduce long-term  government borrowing
since its reduced rates and lower taxes on savings  and investment would boost
economic growth. Each year, the  result would be an expanding tax base and at
least some reduction  in outlays for certain means-tested programs and the 
unemployment compensation system. According to one relatively modest  estimate
of supply-side impact, a flat tax would increase the  economy's long-run annual
growth rate by just 0.5 percent. By the tenth  year, national economic output
would be $578 billion higher than  it would have been without a flat tax. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#21">21</A>
</B></TT> Government's &quot;share&quot;  of this production of additional goods
and services would be $86  billion in tax revenue. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#22">22</A></B></TT>  By the twentieth year,
added growth of  0.5 percent would mean an increase of more than $2 trillion in 
GDP and additional tax revenues in excess of $300 billion.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The revenue feedback from higher growth, however,  probably would not be
enough in the short term to offset the revenue  lost from lower tax rates and
elimination of the multiple taxation  of 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 48 -->  capital income. Achieving a
deficit-neutral flat tax (at least  the Armey version) would require some
restraints on  government spending. And if lawmakers were forced to balance the
budget  by 2002, the limit on spending increases would have to be even  more
stringent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What would happen to the price of other assets?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> While the potentially negative impact on housing markets  and
charity appears negligible, the positive impact on  income-producing assets
would be large. Assets such as stocks, bonds, and  rental properties produce a
stream of income over time. Their  market price is determined by calculating how
much income an asset  will produce over time, after taxes, adjusted to reflect
the fact that  income today is worth more than the same amount of nominal 
income in the future. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#23">23</A></B></TT>
 By lowering tax rates and removing  the double and sometimes triple taxation of
capital income, a flat  tax can increase dramatically the after-tax income
stream an asset  will generate. Thus, a low-rate flat tax would be a boon to
asset  holders, offsetting any theoretical fall in housing prices, and  would
stimulate a surge of new investment in the economy. Harvard  professor and tax
economist Dale Jorgenson estimates that a flat  tax would increase national
wealth by $1  trillion. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#24">24</A></B></TT>
 While this may seem high, it should be remembered that the mere  announcement
in Israel that a capital gains tax was being imposed caused the  Israeli stock
market to drop by 10 percent in just one  day.<TT><B>
<A HREF="ftnt2.htm#25">25</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Would a flat tax benefit everybody?
</B></P>
<P>
</P> 
<P><B>A.</B> If the question is considered narrowly (will anyone's tax  bill
rise?) it depends on how a flat tax is structured. If it is designed  to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 49 -->  give the government as much money
as it receives under the  current system, and if there is no consideration of
the increased  revenue that would accrue from new job creation and higher 
economic growth, then it is impossible to avoid having winners  and losers. In
the long run, a flat tax presumably would generate  higher incomes and living
standards, raising after-tax income even  for those who suffered a short-term
tax increase. At the same time,  it doubtless would have an adverse impact on
the lawyers,  accountants, and lobbyists who profit from the current law's
complexity.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Many flat tax proposals are structured so that few taxpayers,  if any, would
have higher tax bills. This is because they are  designed to go beyond
simplification and rate reduction to include  significant tax cuts for the
American economy. The Armey plan is  a good example. Using static estimating
techniques, it  probably would save taxpayers hundreds of billions of dollars
over a  five-year period. While the combination of a 17 percent tax rate  and
generous family exemption would not necessarily guarantee  lower tax bills for
everyone, few would face higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Is there a way to stop politicians from raising tax rates in  the
future?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> There is no guarantee that a future Congress would not turn  a
simple flat tax back into a complicated &quot;progressive&quot; tax. This  is
the Achilles' Heel of tax reform. The sweeping reform enacted  in 1986 expanded
the tax base by eliminating many deductions  while simultaneously reducing tax
rates to keep the total tax burden  from climbing. Skeptics warned that
politicians could not be trusted  to honor this arrangement and that eventually
they would raise  rates while failing to restore deductions. This is exactly
what  happened 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 50 -->  under Presidents Bush and
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Could this happen with a flat tax?  Using the promise of low  tax rates,
could politicians take away the home mortgage interest  deduction, the
charitable contributions deduction, and other tax  preferences but then raise
tax rates in the future?  It is to reduce  this danger that most proponents of a
flat tax include an ironclad  provision to make raising tax rates difficult or
impossible. One way  to accomplish this would be by amending the Constitution to
 require that no increase in tax rates can be approved without the votes  of at
least three-fifths or two-thirds (in other words, a  &quot;super-majority&quot;)
of both the House and  Senate. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#26">26</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Should the income tax be abolished instead?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Proponents of a flat tax note that the current &quot;progressive&quot;
 income tax penalizes growth, discourages savings and  investment, imposes heavy
compliance costs, destroys jobs, and  reduces America's international
competitiveness. It has been pointed  out, moreover, that a flat rate income tax
reduces but does not  eliminate these negative effects. Thus, the question for
some  becomes whether it would be better to replace the income tax with a sales 
or &quot;consumption&quot; tax. Proponents of this view, including  House Ways
and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer (R-TX)  and Senator Richard Lugar
(R-IN), usually suggest that the  foregone revenue could be offset by spending
cuts, consumption taxes,  or some combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Most advocates of a flat tax recognize that this argument is  sound, at
least in theory. Abolishing the income tax, closing down  the Internal Revenue
Service, and repealing the 16th  Amendment 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 51 -->  clearly would be in the national
interest. Eliminating the  income tax would lead to even more economic growth
and job  creation than would occur under a flat tax. The real question is how 
that goal can be achieved.
</P> 
<P>
</P>
<P>Supporters of the flat tax have decided that eliminating the  income tax is
unlikely, especially in the short run. Because so many  interest groups benefit
from the current tax system, enacting a flat  tax will be difficult by itself.
Moreover, there is some concern  that proposals to abolish the income tax could
play into the hands  of those who want a national sales tax, or value added tax
(VAT),  as an add-on tax. If implemented as a replacement for the income  tax,
either of these would be less destructive to the economy. The  experiences of
other countries, however, suggest that, while a  VAT would be implemented with
the promise to eliminate other  taxes, politicians would never take that second
step. The country  then would have the worst of both worlds: income and direct 
consumption taxes. <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#27">27</A> 
</B></TT>In any event, enacting a flat tax is probably  necessary as an interim
measure for those who favor eliminating the  income tax.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Would a flat tax eliminate the marriage penalty?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Probably, but it depends on how the flat tax is structured.  The
marriage penalty refers to the increased tax faced by a  married couple compared
to two single people with similar incomes.  This penalty is most severe for
couples with similar earnings. A flat  tax automatically solves part of this
problem by making it no  longer possible for one spouse's income to push a
couple into a higher  tax bracket. But the marriage penalty also arises if the
personal  exemption for a married couple is not twice the size of the  exemption

<!-- Generation of PM publication page 52 -->  for those filing singly. The
Armey proposal solves this part of  the problem by giving a married couple twice
the exemption of  a single filer. Nevertheless, a flat tax could be constructed
that  retains this penalty.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. How would a flat tax affect business and payroll taxes?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> It would be possible to reform the personal income tax 
dramatically while leaving the corporate income tax untouched. As  mentioned
earlier, many businesses file using the personal tax code,  so many of their
problems would be solved by a flat tax that left  the corporate tax code
untouched. All flat taxes based on the  Hall/Rabushka model, however, reform
both the personal and  corporate income tax codes. Under the Armey proposal, for
instance,  the business rate would fall to 17 percent, the same as the  personal
rate, and the code would be reformed to eliminate the excess  taxation of
capital.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A flat tax can be designed to include substantial reform of  Social Security
and Medicare payroll taxes. Under current law,  payroll taxes totaling 15.3
percent are levied on the first $61,600 of  income (7.65 percent each from
employer and employee,  though economists agree that the entire tax is borne by
the  worker). <TT><B><A HREF="ftnt2.htm#28">28</A></B></TT>
 Although none has reached legislative form, some flat tax plans  incorporate
the payroll tax, making the total marginal tax rate a  fixed percentage
regardless of income.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Would a flat tax help America compete?
</B></P>
<P>
</P> 
<P><B>A.</B> The historic tax rate reductions launched by Ronald Reagan  in
the 1980s caused a chain reaction around the world. Many  nations 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 53 -->  followed America's example and
have made similarly  dramatic reductions in marginal tax rates in recent years.
In large part,  this worldwide shift in tax policy was driven by competition as 
investors avoided nations with high tax rates. Unfortunately,  America seems to
be one of the few nations that have not learned from  the experience of the
1980s. While the rest of the world has been  cutting taxes, the United States
stands alone as the only major  nation to impose sharply higher tax rates in
recent years. Investors  have reacted accordingly, and the amount of new
investment in  American jobs and business from overseas has dropped from an 
average of $175 billion per year during the low tax years of the 1980s to  an
average of only $108 billion in 1990. <TT><B><A
HREF="ftnt2.htm#29">29</A></B></TT>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What happens to capital gains taxes and estate taxes under a  flat
tax?</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> They are all eliminated. One of the key principles of a flat tax 
is that income is taxed only once. A capital gain for a financial  asset is
simply a reflection that the market's expectation of the  after-tax streams of
income from that asset has risen. Under a flat tax,  that income is taxed at the
business level when it is realized. To tax  the capital gain is double taxation.
Similarly, the estate tax is a  second layer of tax on earning which, under the
current system,  already has been taxed at least once.
</P>
<P>
</P>
