<p><li>
    Alexis de Tocqueville, <i>Democracy in America</i> (New York, N.Y.: Alfred A. Knopf, 1972), Book One, p. 51.
<p><li>
    Wood, <i>Radicalism of the American Revolution,</i> p. 342.
<p><li>
    Thomas Jefferson, <i>Autobiography,</i> p. 51, in <i>The Life and Selected Writings of Thomas Jefferson,</i> ed. Adrienne Koch and William Peden (New York, N.Y.: Random House, 1944).
<p><li>
    Constitution of the United States, Article I, Section 9, paragraph 4.
<p><li>
    John R. Luckey, "A History of Federal Estate, Gift, and Generation-Skipping Taxes," <i>CRS Report for Congress,</i> Congressional Research Service, March 16, 1995, p. 4.
<p><li>
    <i>Pollock v. Farmers' Loan and Trust Company,</i> 158 U.S. 429 (1895).
<p><li>
    The Sixteenth Amendment reads: "The Congress shall have power to lay and collect taxes on income, from whatever source derived, without apportionment among the several States, and without regard to any census or enumeration."
<p><li>
    There is little foundation for a claim that the U.S. government levied taxes on incomes in 1914 because it needed additional revenues. Federal budget surpluses in 1911 and 1912 led to a reduction in total federal debt in 1913 and 1914, and these latter two years had very small deficits of about $400,000 each. Bureau of the Census, <i>Historical Statistics of the United States: Colonial Times to 1970,</i> Part 2, 1975, p. 1104, Series Y, column 336.
<p><li>
