<p><li>
    John Rawls, <i>A Theory of Justice</i> (Cambridge, Mass.: Harvard University Press, 1971).
<p><li>
    <i>Ibid.</i>, p. 303.
<p><li>
    Rawls advances a consumption tax to replace income taxes. "For one thing, it is preferable to an income tax (of any kind) at the level of common sense precepts of justice, since it imposes a levy according to how much a person takes out of the common store of goods and not according to how much he contributes (assuming here that income is fairly earned)." <i>Ibid.</i>, p. 278.
<p><li>
    <i>Ibid.</i>, p. 302.
<p><li>
    <i>Ibid.</i>, p. 279.
